<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT May 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Another telephone exchange was bombed in Eastern
province of Sri Lanka, sources said Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth bomb attack on telephone exchanges in a
month. The previous four bomb attacks occurred in telecom
buildings in Dehiwela, Kalutara, Kuliyapitiya and
Nochchiyagama. (Sri Lanka-Bomb Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Eleven people were injured in clashes between
ultra-Orthodox Jews and Palestinians Sunday in East Jerusalem as
violence marred the Jewish holiday of Shavuot.
</P>
<P>
The clashes broke out as Orthodox Jews passed by the Muslim
Quarter of the Old City after ending their morning prayer at the
Western Wall to celebrate Shavuot, the Jewish festival
commemorating the obtaining of Torah (Five Law Books of Moses) on
Mount Sinai and marking the start of the harvest season.
(Israel-Festival-Clash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Northern Ireland was hit by some of its worst street
violence in more than two years Saturday night as a 400-strong
crowd went on the rampage, according to news from Portadown, Co
Armagh, early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Twelve police officers and three civilians were hurt in a hail
of stones, bottles and petrol bombs in the flashpoint area of
Portadown. (NIreland-Violence)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Flights from British airports are slowly returning to
normal on Sunday after thousands of travelers faced delays because
of a strike by Spanish air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
At Gatwick airport in London, there was an average delay of up
to three hours on flights to Spain or to destinations such as the
United States or Portugal with routes through Spanish airspace.
</P>
<P>
Worst-hit was thought to be Glasgow city airport in Scotland,
where 1,000 passengers were stranded waiting to board holiday
flights as the Spanish ended their strike, but then began a
work-to-rule. (UK-Airports-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Thousands of people were feared dead Sunday after
a strong earthquake measuring 6.9 on the Richter scale jolted
northeastern Afghanistan on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here Sunday from the Afghan capital of Kabul
said that about 50 villages were destroyed in the earthquake which
centered around Rostaq and Faizabad in the mountainous region.
(Pakistan-Afghanistan-Quake Deaths) 
</P>
</TEXT>
