<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Foreign Minister Predicts More Tests by India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani's foreign minister
said on Sunday that his country has no plan for additional
nuclear tests while India is preparing a new site for more
nuclear testing in early July.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with CNN's "Late Edition" program, Gohar
Ayub Khan said from Islamabad that "there is nothing in the cards
for a long time to come" with regard to nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
But he said he has "credible information" that India is "in
the process of preparing a new test site ... to blast somewhere
in the first of second week in July."
</P>
<P>
Khan said Pakistan is ready to sit down with an outside
mediator to try to resolve its problems with India and that U.S.
President Bill Clinton "should have the clout" to bring the two
sides together, particularly on the main issue dividing the two
neighbors, the disputed Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, asked on NBC's
"Meet the Press" if the South Asian rivals would stage more
tests, said: "Obviously, we hope not. We have reason to think
that these two countries, India and Pakistan, as they ponder the
mistakes that they have made over the last couple of weeks, will
understand that they have not enhanced their security. They have
diminished it. They have not enhanced their standing in the
world. they have diminished it."
</P>
<P>
U.S. intelligency sources said on Saturday they had detected no
sign that either Pakistan or India was preparing for further tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
