<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Legislature Warns of No-Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) Sunday warned of a no-confidence vote if the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) failed to formulate the 1998
budget within two weeks, Israeli Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The PLC, announcing the decision in the West Bank city of
Ramallah Sunday, asked the PNA to report the progress on the
formulation of the budget to it in the coming two weeks.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, 28 lawmakers of the 88-seat council, including
several members of Arafat's own Fatah faction, signed a petition
in favor of a no-confidence vote to protest the PNA's failure to
work out the 1998 budget, carry out long-promised reforms against
corruption and mismanagement, and enforce laws passed by the PLC.
</P>
<P>
Apparently to stave off the vote, Arafat signed Thursday five
minor laws passed by the PLC. And a panel on reform has reportedly
been set up.
</P>
<P>
Any no-confidence vote would be the first since the council was
elected in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, political observers here said that the PNA will
survive the no-confidence vote if it comes true because the
majority of the PLC supports Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Even if the motion did pass, it could only lead to a cabinet
reshuffle by Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
