<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Senior Military Leader Visits Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Japanese Joint
Chiefs of Staff Kazuya Natsukawa arrived here Sunday on an
eight-day official visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency said the visit, the first ever by the
top Japanese military leader, would be packed with "numerous
meetings" with Russian military officials.
</P>
<P>
While in Moscow, Natsukawa will meet Russian Defense Minister
Igor Sergeyev, chief of the General Staff Anatoly Kvashnin and
commanders-in-chief of the three services of the Russian armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass said the number of official meetings "substantially
tops the traditional framework of visits of such a level."
</P>
<P>
The trip was made at the initiative of Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, who agreed
at the first informal meeting in Krasnoyarsk last November on an
exchange of visits at the level of the chiefs of general staffs.
</P>
<P>
After Moscow, Natsukawa will go to Vladivostok to meet fleet
commander Mikhail Zakharenko and Primorye governor Yevgeny
Nazdratenko.
</P>
<P>
No joint documents were planned for signing during visit,
Itar-Tass said. The last protocol on bilateral military
cooperation was signed on April 29, 1996 in Moscow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
