<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Vice President Leaves for Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan left for Algeria on Sunday to rally international support
for his country's call for lifting of United Nations economic
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Before departure, Ramadan told the Iraqi News Agency (INA) that
his mission is part of the efforts to inform leaders of friendly
countries about Iraq's ties with the U.N. Security Council and the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) overseeing disarmament of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan, as Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's envoy, will brief
Algerian leaders on the impact of the crippling sanctions on the
Iraqi people and the need of the U.N. Security Council to honor
its obligations toward Iraq, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
He will convey a message to Algerian President Liamine Zeroual
from Saddam on Iraq-Algeria relations, the current Arab situation
and the importance of joint Arab actions to encounter United
States threats and conspiracies against Iraq and the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan said the Security Council should start to carry out
paragraph 22 of the U.N. resolution 687, which provides the
condition on lifting of the trade embargo against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed the economic sanctions on
Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait. Only when the UNSCOM
certifies that Iraq has destroyed all the weapons of mass
destruction, will the world organization lift the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan praised Iraq's "outstanding relations" with Algeria,
saying they will witness broader progress in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
He hailed Algeria's support for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
After Algeria, Ramadan will travel to some other Arab
countries, the agency said. But it did not elaborate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
