<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat: Most Arab States Endorse Proposed Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
said Sunday that most Arab countries have endorsed a Palestinian
proposal to hold an Arab summit to coordinate stances on the
stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return to Gaza from a two-day visit to the United Arab
Emirates (UAE), Arafat told reporters that "very important effort"
is being made to convene the summit very soon because of the
critical situation the peace process is facing.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not say when the summit would be held.
</P>
<P>
Due to the deadlock in the peace process, Arafat has called for
an Arab summit to work out a unified position to encounter
Israel's intransigence and hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
He has intensified his efforts for the summit after the United
States failed to convince Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to accept a proposal on Israeli withdrawal from 13.1
percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Jordan and the UAE have voiced support for the
summit. Latest reports said that the summit is likely to be held
early June in Egyptian capital Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Palestinians and Israelis have been
in a standstill since March 1997 when Israel started construction
of a Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem, which the
Palestinians want as capital of their future independent state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
