<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Still at Crossroads: Executive Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) is still at a crossroads 23 years after
its establishment, Executive Secretary Mouhammadou Ousmane has
said.
</P>
<P>
Ousmane made the remarks in his weekend message in Abuja to
mark the establishment of the sub-regional body on May 28, 1978,
the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He remarked that though ECOWAS has achieved a lot in the past
23 years, there is still room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
Ousmane noted that ECOWAS has made great advance in the sphere
of economic integration, especially in the areas of trade
liberalization and harmonization of customs documents,
regulations and procedures.
</P>
<P>
He cited the free movement of people and the introduction of
the ECOWAS travel certificate as the most notable achievement,
saying that the ECOWAS traveler's check would soon be launched
to facilitate trade transactions.
</P>
<P>
In the area of transport, he said that 83 percent of the
trans-coastal and 87 percent of the trans-Sahelian highways have
been completed, while the communications sector has improved
considerably following the completion of the INTELCOM (I), which
links capital cities in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, ECOWAS has made significant progress in its drug
interdiction effort, the executive secretary said, pointing out
that this has been acknowledged by the United Nations
International Drug Control Program.
</P>
<P>
Ousmane commended the West African peace-keeping force ECOMOG
for keeping the peace in the sub-region, especially in Sierra
Leone and Liberia.
</P>
<P>
In spite of these achievements, he stressed the need to
implement decisions taken by the organizations's leaders so as to
prepare the group for the rapid changes sweeping the world and
for the third millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Short of Strategic Grain Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government has
purchased 43,000 tons of maize worth 1.5 million U.S. Dollars for
the strategic grain reserve this season, failing to hit the
target of 150,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Hamimu Hongo, an official with the Food Security Department in
the President's Office, said that the department is not able to
buy more maize as only one billion shillings has been given by
the treasury.
</P>
<P>
The official, who spoke at a food security workshop here
Sunday, said that maize is still in abundance in many
parts of the country but the funds released for the purchase of
strategic grain reserve have been used up.
</P>
<P>
H. Missano, an official from the Tanzania Food and Nutrition
Center (TFNC), said that about seven million people in the
country face food insecurity chronically. She suggested that
people should plant drought-resistant crops such as sorghum,
cassava and sweet potatoes and improve their grain storage
facilities and exploit forest resources.
</P>
<P>
Representatives at the workshop, which was organized by the
Christian Council of Tanzania, have also suggested people to eat
banana and other fruits so as to increase food supply and avoid
malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania was struck by a drought in 1997 and floods at the
turn of the year. In this season a lot of areas are expected to
have a rice harvest, but the government feels it difficult to
provide food relief to all disaster areas as a lot of roads have
been damaged by floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-31 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: Arab States Hold Intensive Consultations on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Arab countries are making intensive
consultations on holding a summit to seek ways of breaking the
deadlock in the Middle East peace process, Egypt's Presidential
Advisor Osama el-Baz said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"There is a unanimous Arab desire to demonstrate a strong and
permanent Arab attitude," he said.
</P>
<P>
The present crisis in the Middle East peace process will be a
main item of the proposed summit, but other issues of interest to
the Arab nation may also be raised, Baz said, without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
An Arab Summit, which was proposed by Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat, is likely to take place in
Cairo early June to tackle the flagging peace process, Arab
diplomatic sources here said.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, Arafat said on Sunday in
Gaza that "most but not all Arab countries" have agreed to an
emergency summit to close ranks and face up to Israel's
intransigence.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has held talks with leaders of some Arab countries,
including Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Morocco and the United Arab
Emirates (UAE), on the proposed summit. Egypt, Jordan, the UAE and
Saudi Arabia have reportedly agreed to attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been in a standstill since
March 1997 when Israel started construction of a Jewish settlement
in East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as capital of
their future independent state.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks have also been stalled over Israeli troop
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The United States has proposed that Israel withdraw from 13.1
percent of the West Bank. But Israel has not accepted the
proposal, citing security concerns. It maintained that it will
hand over no more than 9 percent of the West Bank to the
Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
