<HEADLINE> Susan McDougal Wants to Study Clinton Testimony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Susan McDougal said she would
have to carefully study President Bill Clinton's testimony before
attesting to whether he spoke the truth in denying knowledge of
illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. McDougal told NBC's "Meet the Press" Sunday in a phone
interview, "I would have to actually have his testimony in front
of me and go through it line by line before I would be willing to
put myself up to say he told the truth."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month her attorney, Mark Geragos, on the same
program, said McDougal, who has refused to provide testimony to
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, would tell a jury that Clinton
had spoken the truth in her 1996 fraud trial.
</P>
<P>
"I would want it to be the actual absolute truth before I would
do that, and I couldn't do that today," she said about confirming
Clinton's truthfulness.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. McDougal served 18 months for civil contempt for refusing
to testify to Starr's Whitewater grand jury. That term ended in
March and she began serving a two-year term for fraud in the
Whitewater real estate case.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. McDougal also denied statements in a recently published
book quoting her late husband Jim McDougal as saying that
President Clinton, at an April 1996 meeting, offered him immunity
in exchange for his cooperation in the Whitewater investigation.
</P>
<P>
"I was with Jim every second from the moment we entered the
White House until the time we left the White House and I can tell
you that conversation never occurred," she said.
</P>
<P>
The McDougals were partners with Bill and Hillary Rodham
Clinton in the Whitewater development when Clinton was governor of
Arkansas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
