<HEADLINE> Egypt Kicks off First Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
switched on the transmission button of the country's first
telecommunications satellite, the Nilesat 101, on Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak gave the go-ahead at one of Nilesat's main control
stations in the 6th of October City, about 30 kilometers southeast
of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The start of the satellite operation crowned a three-hour
ceremony marking the 15th anniversary of the Egyptian Media Day,
which was beamed live by the Egyptian television.
</P>
<P>
According to Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif, there
will be 50 general and specialized television channels, open and
encrypted, to be viewed by Egyptians and Arabs by the use of
small, low-cost dishes over a 90-day experimental period.
</P>
<P>
Nilesat was launched by the Ariane-4 Rocket from the Korou air
space in French Guyana, South America on April 28. It is being
tracked by five ground stations in Egypt, France, South America
and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has already signed contracts with Libya and Oman to lease
its space channels on its first satellite Nilesat. A space channel
is expected to be leased to Lebanon shortly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
