<HEADLINE> Islamic Organization, UAE Concerned over Pakistani, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- An Islamic organization and the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) have expressed deep concern for the
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan and urged them to take
measures to keep security and stability in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, Secretary
General of the Organization of the Islamic Conference Ezzidine
Laraki said that his organization "has always been looking forward
to the establishment of a nuclear-free region in South Asia," the
Kuwaiti News Agency reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Laraki called on the international community to press India and
Pakistan to sign a non-aggression treaty to guarantee security and
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He, in the meantime, warned against using nuclear tests as a
pretext to attack Islamic nations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released on Saturday, the UAE emphasized that
the nuclear tests of India and Pakistan will not serve the
interests of security and stability, but rather aggravate the
tension in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
It called on the two countries to exercise restraint and
resume peace talks to defuse tension and maintain regional peace
and security.
</P>
<P>
The UAE called for comprehensive ban on nuclear tests and
proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, in response to India's five nuclear tests on May 11
and 13, set off five nuclear devices on Thursday and another on
Saturday. The nuclear tests of the two countries have sparked
concern and condemnation in the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
