<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Reacts Strongly to British Report on War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Monday reacted strongly to a
report carried by the Sunday Times over British plans in case of
war on this divided East Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Times reported on Sunday that Britain is planning
the biggest airlift of 250,000 people from Cyprus since the
Second World War because of mounting fears over war if the
Cypriot government proceeds with the deployment of Russian-made
S-300 anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the report, Cypriot government spokesman Christos
Stylianides said in a written statement Monday that such actions
do not contribute to good bilateral relations, adding that the
government decision to deploy the anti-aircraft missiles would not
change.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered the Russian-made surface-to-air
S-300 missile system in January 1997, which is expected to be
deployed later this year.
</P>
<P>
The deal was criticized by the U.S., Britain and some other
countries, and met strong opposition from Turkey, which has
threatened to destroy the missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the Cypriot government "is aware of the
position of the British government regarding the delivery of the
S-300 missiles to Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, however, that the British government was
officially informed of the purchase of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman described the leaking of information by the
British Defense Ministry about plans they have developed in the
event of a crisis in Cyprus as "unusual."
</P>
<P>
"Those who have leaked the information to the press
underestimate our intelligence and determination as well as the
Cypriot people's dignity," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has repeatedly stated that this
defensive missile system will not be deployed if there is
substantial progress in efforts toward a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot south and
the Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
