<HEADLINE> Released Kaunda Vows to Continue with Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Released Zambian former president
Kenneth Kaunda said here Monday that he will continue with his
civil disobedience campaign and be a political rival of President
Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Outside the Lusaka High Court, Kaunda told reporters and
thousands of supporters immediately after his release that he
will continue to be a "thorn" in the side of his successor and
political foe, Chiluba, who took power from Kuanda in the 1991
multi-party elections.
</P>
<P>
"I am still an active politician. I will continue with my
civil disobedience campaign because I was born that way," shouted
the 74-year-old former leader amid the deafening cheers of his
jubilant supporters.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, also leader of Zambia's largest opposition United
National Independence Party (UNIP), launched a countrywide civil
disobedience campaign after he was disqualified as a presidential
candidate because of his foreign parentage.
</P>
<P>
The white-beard veteran statesman who led Zambia to
independence from Britain in 1964 and ruled the country for 27
years walked to freedom from the court Monday morning after the
state dropped all charges that he knew about a coup plot last
October.
</P>
<P>
The release was offered by Chiluba as a deal on condition that
Kaunda agrees to step down from politics, The Post, Zambia's
leading independent newspaper, Monday quoted UNIP and the state
house sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, some western diplomats believed that the release is a
deal brokered by South African President and leader of African
National Congress Nelson Mandela who spent years in exile in
Lusaka as Kuanda's guests, during the years of apartheid in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, who was out of Zambia when the coup took place, was
arrested last December for alleged involvement in the foiled
military coup staged by dozens of junior army soldiers who
attempted to topple the Chiluba government. Kaunda has been
denying the allegations and insisting that he is "innocent".
</P>
<P>
He was transferred to house arrest days after his arrest under
international pressure but later was charged with misprision of
treason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
