<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Fails to Decide on Pullback from West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli cabinet held a
session on Monday to discuss a further troop withdrawal from the
West Bank, but made no decisions.
</P>
<P>
During the session, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
briefed the ministers on the current talks with the Palestinians
and the United States on the issue.
</P>
<P>
But he failed to convince all the ministers to accept a U.S.
proposal aimed at breaking the deadlock in the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly proposed that Israel withdraw from
another 13.1 percent of the West Bank in exchange for the
fulfillment of the Palestinian commitments to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Sources in Jerusalem said that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has urged Israel to make a decision on the
troop pullback in a few days.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, a
leading hawk in the rightwing Likud coalition, has expressed
opposition to the proposed scope of withdrawal, saying that any
pullback of more than 9 percent would jeopardize the security of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu suggested in the meeting that Sharon and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai meet Abu Mazen, deputy head of
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to discuss the issue. But
Sharon and Mordechai rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Meir Sheetrit, Likud whip of Knesset (parliament),
Monday proposed that Netanyahu bring the issue of withdrawal to
the Knesset, despite the objection of the right-wingers.
</P>
<P>
He said that opposition Labor party would support the
government on the issue.
</P>
<P>
In response, Labor Knesset member Haggai Meron said that Labor
should provide a safety net for the government on this issue.
</P>
<P>
But another Labor member Shevah Weiss opposed it, saying that
the Netanyahu government can not bring peace to the country and
the Labor should bring it down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
