<HEADLINE> hke060155 -Philippine President-Elect Lists Priorities in Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President-elect Joseph
Estrada Monday committed to prioritizing the attainment of peace,
the modernization of the armed forces and the improvement of the
living standards of the soldiers and personnel.
</P>
<P>
Estrada bared the three top priorities in defense and security
matters during a closed-door meeting with outgoing President Fidel
Ramos and top military officers in what was considered one of the
briefings initiated by Ramos for the incoming administration.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said his administration is determined to enhance the
security and military capabilities of the armed forces by fully
implementing the long-term modernization of the forces.
</P>
<P>
However, incoming Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado clarified
that the next administration cannot immediately release the funds
for the purchase of two modern planes for the armed forces as
requested by outgoing presidential national security adviser Jose
Almonte.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said the next administration will still have to review
the terms of the sale and determine whether the modern planes will
play a key role in the modernization of the military.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Estrada committed to pursuing the peace
process by continuing the peace talks initiated by the Ramos
administration with the rebels in the country.
</P>
<P>
"My incoming administration is determined to pursue the peace
process, more so the implementation of peace and development
programs that would spell the lasting solution to these
insurgencies," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to fulfill the pledge in the election campaigns,
the President-elect said he would also push for a package of
measures to improve the living standards of soldiers and AFP
personnel.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier meeting, Estrada was briefed on the national
security situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Estrada gained an overwhelming victory in the May 11 elections.
He would assume office on June 30 when Ramos' term expires.
</P>
</TEXT>
