<HEADLINE> S. African Exports to US Surge in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- South African exports to the
United States surged in the first quarter of this year, slashing
South Africa's trade deficit with the United States, the latest
Commerce Ministry figures showed.
</P>
<P>
Measured by customs value, U.S. imports from South Africa
between January and March hit 720 million U.S. Dollars -- a 45
percent leap from the equivalent figure last year, while U.S.
exports to South Africa grew by just two percent to 729 million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The nine million Dollars' South African deficit represented a
96 percent narrowing of the 222 million Dollars trade gap a year
ago, Business Day paper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. imports of South African platinum group metals and gold
products were up 58 percent on a year ago to 278 million Dollars.
This included 166 million Dollars worth of platinum sponge, up
from 114 million Dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Despite U.S. anti-dumping action against South African carbon
steel plate, South African iron and steel exports to the United
States were up 88 percent to 124 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter also saw increased deliveries to the United
States of ore, inorganic chemicals, industrial machinery and
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
However, South Africa's clothing exports to the United States,
including fabric and clothing, declined in the first quarter
compared with a year ago, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
