<HEADLINE> Qingdao Lures More Foreign Funds in First Four Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- This coastal city in east China's
Shandong Province achieved an 81.9 percent rise in the
introduction of contractual overseas capital in the first four
months of this year, despite the current financial turmoil in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attribute this success to the city's
newly-launched "Soothing and Enriching Businessmen" program.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the financial crisis started, the city government
set up a special mechanism to closely monitor its direct or
indirect impacts on the local economy.
</P>
<P>
The municipal commission on foreign trade and economic
cooperation has listed 58 foreign-funded companies for special
concern. So far, 22 of these firms have been granted loans so
as to help them get over their current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, local taxation bureaus have delayed or exempted the
payment of taxes for some of these companies.
</P>
<P>
These foreign-funded firms have also been given preferential
treatment in exporting and employment. 
