<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Defends Interest Rate Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 1 (Xinhua) - Malaysia's central bank said
Monday that its interest rate policy continued to be aimed at
balancing the need to maintain price stability and a stable
exchange rate while ensuring productive activity.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, (an) appropriate macroeconomic policy,
including (an) interest rate policy, is important for overall
confidence of the economic and financial system," Bank Negara, the
central bank, said in a statement on its current monetary stance
in light of issues that have been raised on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
It said that at the current interest rates, this balance was
being addressed within the comprehensive set of policies adopted
in December 1997 and March this year.
</P>
<P>
In promoting macroeconomic, financial stability and the
recovery of the economy, Malaysia has relied on a broad spectrum
of measures other than interest rates alone, it said.
</P>
<P>
While recognizing that borrowing costs had increased during the
current period and produced strains on the overall economy,
Malaysia also considered exchange rate stability to be an
important element in the recovery process, it said.
</P>
<P>
Of late, there have been calls from many quarters for lending
rates to be lowered in order to stimulate an economic recovery as
they contend that the current rates at around 16 percent were
stifling businesses and had caused the cost of doing business to
rise.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that in the current environment, inflationary
pressures needed to be contained so as to preserve the domestic
purchasing power, especially for the lower and medium income
groups.
</P>
<P>
It said that containing inflationary pressures and promoting
exchange rate stability were necessary to rebuild market
confidence and maintain international competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"At the current interest rate level, the real rate of return on
deposits (after taking into account the expected rate of
inflation) is being maintained at levels prevailing before the
crisis," the bank said, adding that this has allowed savings in
Malaysia to continue to be efficiently mobilized through the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
Appropriate interest rate levels were also necessary to contain
the outflows of funds, it added.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said several initiatives had been taken to
correct the distortions that have resulted in lending rates being
higher than necessary despite a tighter monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
It said initiatives had also been taken to provide productive
sectors with access to financing at reasonable rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
