<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabian Crown Prince
Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz wrapped up his two-day visit to Syria
Monday and left for Jordan, the second leg of his current
three-nation tour aimed at coordinating stances on a proposed Arab
summit.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Abdullah held talks with Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad and Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam on ways of
breaking the deadlock in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here said that Abdullah exchanged views with
Syrian leaders on the convening of an Arab summit. They also
discussed the adoption of a unified Arab stance toward the stalled
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah's visit to Syria is part of a regional tour, which
will also take him to Egypt. The trip is aimed at coordinating
positions on holding an emergency Arab summit to deal with the
Israeli intransigence and hardline policy on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Media reports have said that most Arab states have agreed to
the convocation of the summit.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic sources said that Syria and Saudi Arabia have
identical views on the need for an Arab summit in view of the
delicate and sensitive conditions prevailing the region.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah was also seeking to rectify the relations between
Syria, on the one hand, and Jordan and the Palestinians, on the
other.
</P>
<P>
The relations have been cool due to the Palestinians' efforts
to make peace with Israel since 1993 and Jordan's signing of a
peace treaty with the Jewish state in 1994. 
