<HEADLINE> Flood Devastates Russia's Siberian Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 1 (Xinhua) -- At least 15 people have died in a
flood caused by the ice thaw of the Lena, Aldan, Olekma and Amga
rivers in Russia's Siberian region of Yakutia Sakha.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass reported Monday that about 15,000 houses in 163
settlements with a population of 475,000 are inundated. Half of
the more than 100,000 people affected by the flood have been
evacuated, the agency quoted an official with the Ministry of
Civil Defense and Emergency Situations as saying.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 bridges were damaged and 900 kilometers of
electricity transmission lines disrupted. More than 2,000
kilometers of roads and 200 dam walls were demolished, and about
3,500 cattle died.
</P>
<P>
Repair work is underway in some regions and humanitarian aid is
being distributed among the victims, Itar-Tass said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
