<HEADLINE> FedEx Announces Expansion Plans for Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Federal Express (FedEx) of the US
revealed a packet of expansion plans here today that will improve
its express pick-up and delivery service within China, including
adding another cargo gateway to the company's business network and
opening three customer service centers in China.
</P>
<P>
"China is a huge market geographically, and the express segment
continues to grow faster than almost any other in the world. For that
reason, we are eager to see a more expanded FedEx business here,"
said John Quinn, vice-president of FedEx's Greater China and
Mid-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
According to Quinn, Chinese customers can count on an expansion
of flight coverage by the end of this year. In addition to the
current flights to Beijing and Shanghai, FedEx is adding a flight
to Shenzhen in Guangdong Province later this year, making the
city the third China cargo gateway served by the company.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, on June 4 FedEx will launch three more customer
service centers in China -- in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou,
respectively. Several toll-free telephone numbers are also being
introduced in the centers, to provide easy access for customers
in neighboring areas.
</P>
<P>
FedEx currently serves more than 30 countries and regions in
the Asia-Pacific region with approximately 5,000 employees. The
company started express operations early in 1984 through local
agents, and was authorized by the Civil Aviation Administration of
China as the only US-based all-cargo carrier with an operating
permit for direct US-China services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
