<HEADLINE> Saudi Crown Prince in Jordan for Preparation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn
Abdul-Aziz arrived here Monday on the second leg of his
diplomatic tour to prepare an Arab summit on the stalled Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi crown prince will meet Jordan's King Hussein and
Crown Prince Hassan late Monday night, the official Radio Jordan
reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister for Development and Minister
of Foreign Affairs Jawad Anani confirmed on Sunday that such a
Arab summit will aim "to overcome Arab divisions."
</P>
<P>
In principle, Jordan supports the idea of holding an Arab
summit, provided that it delivers a positive message, Anani added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and bilateral
cooperation has been conducted in the fields of trade, airport
construction and water supply.
</P>
<P>
Despite the cooperation, Jordan joined the Arab chorus of
condemnation of the Israeli government for its refusal to
implement the peace accords it signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi crown prince arrived from Syria, where he urged the
United States to back a just and legitimate settlement to the
long-stalled Mideast peace process and called on Israel to
acknowledge Arab rights.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Jordan Times Monday quoted anonymous Arab
diplomats as saying that the Saudi crown prince's visit to Amman
aims to reconcile the views of Syria and Jordan, which fears that
an Arab summit will put brakes on its normalization of ties with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
His diplomatic efforts followed the visit of Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat to Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) to garner support for such a summit aimed at forming a
united front against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Saturday visited Saudi
Arabia and put forward comprehensive proposals for the summit.
</P>
<P>
The summit might be attended by Egypt, Jordan, Morocco, Oman,
the Palestinians, Saudi Arabia and the UAE, Jordan Times quoted
reports from Cairo as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations have been deadlocked
for more than a year over the construction of a Jewish settlement
in Arab East Jerusalem. Recent efforts by the U.S. failed to
bridge the gap between the two sides after Israel refused a
U.S. proposal calling for a 13.1 percent of Israeli troop
withdrawal from the West Bank. 
</P>
