<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Determine Tempo of Mass Extinction 250 Million Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and US scientists have
jointly determined the tempo of a mass extinction of life more
than 250 million years ago. About 90 percent of species on Earth
disappeared in a period of 200,000 years.
</P>
<P>
This was the conclusion of scientists who tested zircon from
Late Permian and Early Triassic rocks from Leping County in
east China's Jiangxi Province. The results of the study have been
published in the US journal ``Science''.
</P>
<P>
"New studies show that the catastrophe was more violent than
people believed before," said Jin Yugan, a researcher at the
Nanjing Institute of Geology and Paleontology, under the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"The peak period of the disaster was less than 200,000 years, a
wink in the 4.6 billion-year history of the earth," said Jin.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said the climate of the earth was dry and hot during
the disaster, with rivers and lakes drying up, forests wiped out,
the sea level down to a record low, about 85 percent of the
species living in the oceans and 70 percent of the vertebrate
genera on land snuffed out.
</P>
<P>
"The mass extinction at the end of Permian Age was the most
profound in the history of life, surpassing the one symbolized by
the extinction of the dinosaurs 65 million years ago in terms of
its scale and impact on the evolution of life," added Jin.
</P>
<P>
The earth has witnessed five such huge mass extinctions in its
history, and the cause remains a mystery. Some scientists believe
they were caused by the impact of asteroids or comets.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever happened, it happened very quickly," said Douglas
Erwin of the National Museum of Natural History in Washington,
D.C., who also took part in the joint research.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
