<HEADLINE> Brazil Remains Unbeaten in Volleyball World League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- As the preliminary round entered
halfway, Brazil became the only unbeaten team after six matches
with lots of surprises emerged from the men's volleyball world
league till Monday.
</P>
<P>
In Pool A, Cuba experienced defeat for the first time in the
competition as they lost both matches against Spain. Spanish home
team performed its beat matches until now, with an overwhelming
3-0 win in the first match and a more tight success in the second,
achieving victory in the tie-break with the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
After the second match, Spanish coach Juan Diaz was
delighted: "Today's match is the one we were all waiting for. This
victory reinforces our conviction that with work we can obtain our
best competitive shape."
</P>
<P>
The players of Bulgaria dedicated thier double victory against
South Korea to coach Stefan Sokolov who had his 41st birthday this
weekend. After the second match, Sokolov said "The Korean team
played very well and used good combinations in attack, but we won
thanks to our strong team spirit."
</P>
<P>
In Pool B, Italy and the Netherlands shared honors in their
double header. In Rome, more than 10,000 spectators witnessed the
3-0 victory of the Orange team against their favorites who were
never able to enter the match. Dutch coach Toon Gebrands said that
"our goal was to win one match against Italy to get the access to
the semifinals. We did it and we are very happy."
</P>
<P>
The situation turned over in Siena's crowded Sports Hall when
the Italians struck back and beat the Olympic champions 3-0 in the
second match.
</P>
<P>
Big surprises in Argentina where local team defeated by Greece
3-2, 3-1. The Greeks who took advantage of good services and
better defence also won the second match, showing an impossible
equation to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
In Pool C, Brazil attracted a record attendance of 14,650 in
Rio de Janeiro against Russia. After five matches in this
competition without losing a single set, the South American
conceded the first one to the Russian during their second match,
winning yet easily the double header.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian coach Radames Lattari said that he preferred the
second match because his players had to face a stronger resisting
from the opponent. "I want to give experience to my youngest
players because I know the matches will be harder in Europe," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia and Poland shared the points, with a 3-0 victory for
the host team in the first match and 3-2 success of the visitors
in the second.
</P>
<P>
The Polish coach Ireuneucz Mazur said "I must say that we were
surprised twice during this weekend: first Friday when the
Yugoslav had their almost strongest line-up and the second when
some of the best players did not appear today. Still, now we can
see the importance of Grbic brothers in the Yugoslav team. Their
absence enabled us to stabilise our game and little by little win
this second match. I am very happy for it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
