<HEADLINE> India's 1998-99 Defense Budget Increases Over 14 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- India's 1998-99 budget for
defense has increased by over 14 percent from the previous year's
360.99 billion rupees (9.38 billion U.S. dollars) to 412 billion
rupees (10.70 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Presenting the 1998-99 budget (from April 1,1998 to March 31,
1999) to Parliament here Monday, Indian Finance Minister Yashwant
Sinha said that he would consider further increase in the
budgetary support during the course of the year, if necessary.
"There can be no compromise in our defense preparedness," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said that the plan allocation for Department of Atomic
Energy is being enhanced by 68 percent from 8.28 billion rupees
(0.22 billion dollars) to 13.91 billion rupees (0.36 billion
dollars) and the plan allocation for the Department of Space is
being raised by 62 percent from 8.5 billion rupees (0.22 billion
dollars) to 13.81 billion rupees (0.36 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Department of Atomic Energy has made bigger contributions
to India's five successive nuclear tests on May 11 and 13 this
year.
</P>
<P>
The total Central plan outlay in the 1998-99 budget is at
1,051.87 billion rupees (27.32 billion dollars) from last year's
810.33 billion rupees (21.05 billion dollars) while the total
expenditure is estimated at 2,681.07 billion rupees (69.64 billion
dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first regular budget of the Bharatiya Janata Party
(BJP)-led government in the wake of economic sanctions imposed on
India by The United States, Japan, etc. after it conducted its
five nuclear tests recently.
</P>
<P>
According to a government's economic survey in 1997-98, the
economic situation in the country was in bad shape. Overall
economic growth slowed down to 5 percent in 1997-98 and
agricultural growth was negative. Growth of industrial production
also slackened to 4.2 percent and export growth registered less
than 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, India's fiscal deficit worsened to 6.1 percent
of GDP, the capital market remained in the doldrums and
infrastructure bottlenecks continued to plague the economy,
according to the survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
