<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Electronics Industry Faces Major Restructuring (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China's electronics industry is
to undergo major restructuring to help it shed surplus capacity and
concentrate resources on hi-tech products.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Beijing-based Research Center of the Computer
and Microelectronics Industrial Development (CCID) said that the
household electronic appliance sector is plagued by overcapacity,
while a huge market for hi-tech products is yet to be tapped in
China.
</P>
<P>
At present, China's color TV production lines have a total
capacity of more than 45 million color TV sets every
year, but only 46.1 percent of the capacity is used.
</P>
<P>
Only 50.1 percent of the country's production lines of
refrigerators are working. The rate is even lower for factories
making air-conditioners, range hoods, vacuum cleaners and
washing machines.
</P>
<P>
Local industry experts say that the Chinese government has
adopted a policy of letting market competition regulate the
electronics industry, but it has not adopted effective measures
to prevent over-lapping investment in similar projects.
</P>
<P>
For example, since the beginning of the 1990s, several
localities such as Tianjin, and Shandong, Jiangsu and Guangdong
provinces have set up color TV production bases capable of turning
out millions of sets every year. A joint venture in Shanghai
alone has a production capacity of three million sets a year.
</P>
<P>
However, the hi-tech sector of the country's electronics
industry lacks such large-sized enterprises. The biggest personal
computer (PC) producer in China, the Legend Group, turned out
400,000 PCs in 1997, while the domestic market for PCs was
increasing by one million every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Processing Park for Exports to Russia in Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A products-processing park for
exports to Russia went into operation today in the Economic and
Technological Development Zone in this capital city of northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The park is the first in the country specializing in products
for export to Russia, and features integrated technological
development, production and commerce.
</P>
<P>
The park will make use of resources from northeast China and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Both domestic and overseas enterprises located in the park will
enjoy preferential policies granted by the Chinese government,
involving tax reduction and exemption for raw material imports,
storage of goods and other aspects.
</P>
<P>
The park is expected to improve and increase China's exports to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 300 enterprises with overseas funds from 26 countries
and regions have been set up in the park involving more than 1.3
billion US dollars in total investment. 
</P>
