<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Electronics Industry Faces Major Restructuring (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By April this year, the number of China's mobile telephone
users had exceeded 16 million. The figure is still growing at an
annual rate of 100 percent. However, China will not put into
operation its first wholly-owned mobile phone plant until
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
China now produces less than one fourth of the eight billion
integrated circuits that it uses every year. About 80
percent of those made in China are from plants wholly or
partially owned by foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Local experts said that the imbalance of product structure has
become a major restricting factor for the electronics
industry. They said that overcapacity in certain sectors is a
waste of resources. Therefore, the industry has no way out apart
from restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Market competition has already forced a number of local
electronics giants to readjust their development strategies. Major
TV manufacturers such as Changhong, Hai'er and TCL have diversified
their business into information technology. They have developed
new products such as digital TV sets and multimedia computer
terminals.
</P>
<P>
There is a rising trend in the industry for computer and
electronic appliance manufacturers to mix their businesses.
</P>
<P>
An official from the former Ministry of the Electronics Industry
said that the industry has two major issues to address: One is to
beef up local enterprises' research and development muscle; the
other is to increase input into commercialization of new
technologies.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, China should place manufacturing of
whole sets of computers on the basis of self-developed integrated
circuits, so as to foster its own copyrighted products.
</P>
<P>
China's electronics and integrated circuits industry had a
total output of 380 billion yuan (about 100 billion US
dollars)-worth in 1997. The figure is expected to reach 700
billion yuan-worth in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Before 1997, profits in the industry had remained flat
as output kept increasing. As a result of restructuring, the
industry saw an 10.8 percent increase of profits before tax in
1997 over 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Launch Tree Planting Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Forest Department of Bangladesh
will launch a nation-wide tree planting campaign on June 15, the
national news agency BSS reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Forest Department aims to achieve its objective of planting
at least two trees -- one fruit-bearing tree and one fine wood
tree -- at every house of the country, BSS quoted forest
conservator of Dhaka Central Circle Monzurul Karim as saying.
