<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Iran to Intensify Efforts on Afghan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan said here Monday that Pakistan and Iran will intensify
their joint efforts for the acceleration of the Afghan peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Gohar, who greeted his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi at
the Islamabad airport Monday afternoon, said in a statement that
the Iranian foreign minister's visit "is part of regular high
level consultations between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
"Our talks would follow up on the discussions held between our
leaders on the sidelines of the 5th Summit of the Economic
Cooperation Organization in Almaty last month," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We would particularly focus on the situation in Afghanistan
with a view to promoting intra-Afghan dialogue and a peaceful
solution of the conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We would seek to intensify our joint efforts for the
acceleration of the peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
They would also discuss the expansion of bilateral trade and
economic linkages including the Pakistan-Iran gas pipeline and oil
refinery projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
The general security situation in the region, arising out of
the recent developments, would also come under review, he said.
</P>
<P>
In early May, Afghanistan's Taliban militia and their rival
Northern Alliance held here their first face-to-face talks in over
a year under the auspices of the United Nations and the
Organization of the Islamic Conference. However the talks were
suspended as the two sides refused to make any compromise with
each other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
