<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Japan Plan Joint Naval Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Japan plan to hold joint
naval exercises at the end of next month, the first yet, Itar-Tass
news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The war games will be held soon after naval ships of both
countries take part in festivities in Vladivostok on July 26,
commemorating Navy Day, the agency quoted well-informed sources in
Tokyo as saying.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the exercises is to practice joint search and rescue
operations in the northern part of the Sea of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Russia's big anti-submarine ship, Admiral Nakhimov, of the
Pacific Fleet, is expected to join the maneuvers. Military
officers of both countries will meet again in July in Vladivostok
to work out details of the exercises, Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Military relations between Russia and Japan have warmed up in
recent years. In July 1996, the Japanese torpedo boat, Kurama,
sailed to Vladivostok to take part in celebrations for the 300th
anniversary of the Russian fleet.
</P>
<P>
Last June, Russian's Admiral Nakhimov anti-submarine ship paid
an official visit to Japan, the first such visit in a century.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Chairman of the Japanese Council of
Joint Chiefs of Staff Kazuya Natsukawa held meetings with his
Russian counterpart, Anatoly Kvashnin, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on prospects for development of bilateral
relations between countries in the Asia-Pacific region for the
purpose of multilateral cooperation, Interfax news service
reported. It quoted sources with the Russian Defense Ministry.
</P>
</TEXT>
