<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ``China to Be Scientific Power by 2050'' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Lu Yongxiang, president of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), said today that China is
expected to meet advanced world scientific and technological
standards by 2050 and become a strong power in this sphere.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a work report at the Ninth Conference of CAS
academicians that opened today, Lu said Chinese scientists and
researchers will handle key scientific issues involving the
national economy, social development and national security by
themselves at that time, and basically meet the needs of the
knowledge-based economy.
</P>
<P>
He said China will be a moderately developed nation in the
middle of the next century, and the CAS has formulated a scientific
development strategy in line with Deng Xiaoping's requirement that
"scientific and technological work must take the lead."
</P>
<P>
In 10 years' time, the CAS will put more effort into some key
fast-developing scientific topics with Chinese characteristics,
while China will also try to increase its capability of improving and
absorbing technology, and combine science and the economy better, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
However, insufficient input still restrains China's
scientific and technological development, Lu said, adding that to
solve the problem requires joint efforts of the government,
enterprises and various social sectors in addition to the
scientific sector itself.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
