<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Monday:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- A tornado that struck South Dakota without warning on
Saturday night has wiped out most of a small farming community,
killing six people and destroying its post office, fire station,
library, bank and all four churches. The region was also pelted
with hail the size of chicken eggs.
</P>
<P>
-- The United States would support new international financial
aid to the Government of President Boris N. Yeltsin if Russian
could not meet its short-term debts, President Clinton said,
because a meltdown of the ruble could threaten the stability of
the government there.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton may drop his court appeal on executive
privilege Monday, possibly short-circuiting independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr's bid to bring the case directly to the Supreme
Court, but also allowing Starr to summon senior White House aides
back to the grand jury, sources close to the situation said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign ministers from the five major nuclear states, which
are the U.S., Russia, China, Britain and France, are expected to
demand that India and Pakistan agree to halt tests, keep nuclear
warheads off missiles, avoid transferring technology, order a
moratorium on production of bomb material, and begin Kashmir talks.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
A day after spawning a tornado that killed six people and
destroyed tiny Spencer in South Dakota, a massive storm system
moved through the Northeast Sunday, punishing the region with more
twisters, hail and rain. The six people died Saturday in Spencer
brought the national tornado death toll this year to 121 -- the
worst since 1984. 
</P>
