<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Calls for Revitalizing Kenya's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
Monday called strongly for revitalizing the country's battled
economy when celebrating the 35th anniversary of self-governance
in pomp and color.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 people poured into downtown Nairobi's Uhuru
Park in the morning of Madaraka Day to observe grand celebrations
featured by a march-past by members of the Armed Forces, a
fly-past by Kenya Air Force jets, and songs and colorful
traditional dancers.
</P>
<P>
The day marks the occasion when Kenya secured internal
self-government from the British colonialists and was firmly on
course to independence six months later on December 12, 1963.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation, Moi said the most critical challenges
Kenya faces are poverty and high unemployment rate. More than 45
percent of Kenya's nearly 30 million population now live below
the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
"We have achieved much during the past 35 years but the war
against poverty has yet to be won," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Unemployment has been on the increase mainly because of the
economic difficulties we have experienced since the beginning of
this decade. The situation has been further worsened by reduced
levels of investment," Moi noted.
</P>
<P>
The president listed measures to reduce "excessively high
interest rates," improve tax revenue collection, strengthen
combats against corruption and crimes as top priorities in the
nation-wide efforts to jump-start the economy and the security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called for closer cooperation in eastern Africa,
saying Kenya has always been ready to devoted itself to mediating
in regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Moi also expressed concern about the rising tension between
Ethiopia and Eritrea over a border row, adding that Kenya is
willing to assist in finding a peaceful solution to their
dispute.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff General Daudi Tonje, cabinet ministers
and foreign diplomats were present at the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
