<HEADLINE> Service Center Established to Facilitate Cross-Straits Exchanges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- This special economic zone in east
China's Fujian Province today established a Taiwan-affairs legal
service center to help facilitate cross-Taiwan Straits exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The center specializes in handling Taiwan-related legal affairs
and will provide services on issues pertinent to investment,
enterprise mergers and takeovers, business credibility, rights
infringement, trade, finance, real estate, tourism, personal
visits, cultural exchanges and marriage, among other things,
according to a city government official.
</P>
<P>
The center will also organize or sponsor cross-Straits seminars
and training programs, he added.
</P>
<P>
The center will help Taiwan compatriots to conduct economic,
trade, investment and other activities on the mainland and protect
their legitimate rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics indicate that economic ties across the
Taiwan Straits have increased in recent years, with bilateral
trade hitting 19.8 billion US dollars-worth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan is also Xiamen's second-largest source of external
investment, next only to Hong Kong. Xiamen had approved a total of
1,507 Taiwan-funded projects by February this year, with paid-in Taiwan
investment totaling more than two billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Xiamen and Taiwan reached 1.6 billion
US dollars-worth last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
