<HEADLINE> Iran Opposes Sanctions Against Pakistan: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said here Monday Iran would not endorse the sanctions
imposed by western major powers against Pakistan for its nuclear
explosions following India's similar tests.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi, who is on his first trip to Pakistan since he assumed
the office last year, told reporters at the Islamabad airport that
Iran, as a friendly country, understands Pakistan's security
concerns.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has "no other option but to go nuclear" after India
had conducted the nuclear tests, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But at the same time, we believe that there should be more
restraint in the region and reduction of tension," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran has been following the recent developments in the
region and, "my country is available to bring back more restraint
and reduce tension in the region."
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question on reports that Iran was also planning
to develop nuclear weapons, the Iranian foreign minister said,
Tehran's nuclear program is absolutely for peaceful purposes.
</P>
<P>
Iran's nuclear installations are open to international
inspections which were regularly conducted by International Atomic
Energy Agency (IAEA), he added. 
</P>
