<HEADLINE> Arabs Favor Single Stand Towards Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Arab world is increasingly
intended to form a unified stance to save the dying peace process,
visiting Arab League (AL) chief said monday.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid told reporters here
that contacts are still needed to hold a proposed Arab summit on
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after meeting with Lebanese Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri on regional situation, especially the stalled peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Arab world intensified efforts to help reactivate the
stalled peace process after the failure of the latest round of
U.S. peace mediation.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalemated since March
last year because of Israel's expansion of settlement in East
Jerusalem and the delayed withdrawal of troops from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Arab summit is designed to hammer out an action
plan to deal with Israel's intransigence, Abdel-Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
He came here on Sunday to attend a meeting of nine Arab foreign
ministers. The meeting is served to devise a common Arab strategy
ahead of the convening of the European-Mediterranean partnership
summit in Italy later this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
