<HEADLINE> Leading Officials Urged To Stop Extravagance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Leading officials at all levels
should take the lead in carrying out the anti-extravagance rules
recently formulated by the Central Commission of the Communist
Party of China for Discipline Inspection.
</P>
<P>
In the next few months, local Party committees and governments
should work harder to achieve the anti-corruption goals set by
the commission.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and secretary of the CPC
Central Disciplinary Commission, made these remarks during his
inspection tour of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region in south
China from May 24-June 1.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Guangxi, Wei visited a number of local
villages, factories and hi-tech development projects and held
talks with local officials.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Wei urged local authorities to deal with major
corruption cases and punish corrupt officials. Analyses should be
made of typical cases, so as to sum up the experience in this
sphere and educate officials, he noted.
</P>
<P>
During his tour, Wei, also chairman of the All-China Federation
of Trade Unions, met with local trade union leaders and urged
that they assist local governments in resolving problems related
to factory lay-offs. 
