<HEADLINE> S. Africa Imposes Travel Ban on UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Monday announced
a travel ban on members of the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), a major opposition party in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Individuals known to be senior UNITA officials and their adult
family members would be refused admission of transit through the
country, Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi said in
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement that the sanctions, with effect from
March 18, were imposed in terms of a United Nations resolution
against UNITA last year.
</P>
<P>
In compliance with the U.N. sanctions, South Africa would also
refuse all applications by UNITA members or their families for
visas, immigration permits or the extension of temporary
residence permits.
</P>
<P>
"Temporary residence permits that have already been granted
will be canceled in line with the stipulations of the U.N.
resolution," Buthelezi added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
