<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: British Expatriate Working for SAR Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- When Hong Kong's Postmaster
General Robert Footman attended an Asian Pacific Postal Union
(APPU) meeting in Vietnam in September last year, it was a big
surprise for many people to see a European face in the Chinese
delegation.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the British expatriate sat at the table
representing China at the APPU.
</P>
<P>
"There was a feeling of historic change. That's a very powerful
feeling so you'll take photographs," Footman recalled while
showing photographs of that special moment.
</P>
<P>
"It felt quite strange, suddenly for me, to represent China.
But you don't feel that strangeness after a few minutes when you
sit down and join it (the Chinese delegation)," Footman told
Xinhua at his office in Central.
</P>
<P>
Footman said the Chinese delegation was a "very friendly" one
and he already knew some mainland colleagues before joining it.
</P>
<P>
He said it was a big surprise for many people to see him with
the Chinese delegation, adding that his friends from other postal
administrations "had a broad smile on their face" and "recognized
that it was really a change."
</P>
<P>
"It was pretty a surprise, but it was very positive," said
Footman, who has served various government posts in more than 20
years of public service.
</P>
<P>
Appointed Hong Kong's postmaster general in late 1995, Footman
stayed in the post after Hong Kong's handover to serve the Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government of the People's Republic of
China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the changes brought to Hongkong Post by the
handover, Footman said that since July 1, 1997, representatives
from Hongkong Post have continued participating in the activities
of the Universal Postal Union (UPU) and the APPU as members of the
Chinese delegation. Formerly, Hong Kong joined the British
delegation at UPU meetings and was an observer with the APPU.
</P>
<P>
"Those were changes brought by the handover for us in the post
office. From my point of view that (the post-handover arrangement)
worked very well," Footman said.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Post has been playing a significant role in Hong
Kong's development as a leading commercial, financial and
industrial center, by offering reliable, efficient and universal
services, Footman said.
</P>
<P>
Operating as a trading fund department, Hongkong Post remains a
separate postal administration after the handover, which means
"business as usual," said the 45-year-old SAR official.
</P>
<P>
"We set our postal rates so we continue to have Hong Kong
rates, we issue our stamps, carry out our financial arrangements
with other postal administrations and sign new agreements, and I
continue to meet colleagues in other administrations," Footman
said, adding that this is exactly what the "one country, two
systems" concept has suggested.
</P>
<P>
And for the public of Hong Kong, Footman said, "Life has
continued very much after July 1 as it was before July 1."
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the transition year had an impact on nearly
every government department and service, in the sense that "the
workload went up." The year meant a lot of extra work in
particular for the 5,900 staff members of Hongkong Post.
</P>
<P>
There were a number of things to do, Footman said, like the
design of the new definitive stamps which can be used both before
and after July 1, to replace the old ones bearing the British
queen's head.
</P>
<P>
The new definitive stamp series, featuring a stretch of the
waterfront of the Hong Kong Island, has a neutral design with no
connotation of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"It was not difficult, but it was extra work. There were a lot
of little things like that," Footman said, who highly appreciated
the work attitude of his staff.
</P>
<P>
From time to time workload doubled, but staff didn't, he said.
During the five-day holiday spanning the handover, Hong Kong post
offices were open for the issue of special stamps and souvenir
sheets. At least 4,000 staff were reported for duty during that
period.
</P>
<P>
Recently there was a large volume of mails coming from the
first Legislative Council elections of the SAR and quite a few of
deliveries were required on Sundays just to clear the mail
backlog.
</P>
<P>
Having a family tradition of working overseas, the Cambridge
graduate came to Hong Kong and joined the government as an
administrative officer in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Before being appointed to head Hongkong Post, which he
described as "an extraordinary organization," Footman had served
in a number of government departments which gave him a wide range
of experience that "few careers can give."
</P>
<P>
"I'm lucky that I have a lot of very exciting and challenging
jobs over the years. I'm very happy. In the foreseeable future I
will continue to serve the Hong Kong government," Footman said.
</P>
<P>
He married a Hong Kong Chinese, now a judicial administrator,
and has two sons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
