<HEADLINE> SAARC Chairman on Situation in the Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Maldivian President and SAARC
Chairman Maumoon Abdul Gayoom on Monday called upon all parties
concerned to exercise maximum restraint and make every possible
effort to contain the situation in the region following separate
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on the recent developments in the region, Gayoom
said that SAARC (South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation)
was set up with the important aim of promoting the welfare of the
peoples of South Asia, improving the quality of their life,
enhancing collective self-reliance and contributing to mutual
trust among the seven member countries.
</P>
<P>
A number of significant and positive steps towards the
achievement of these goals had been taken in the past 13 years,
and in particular, during the 9th SAARC summit held in May 1997 in
Male, capital of the Maldives, said the statement from the
Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, in view of the momentum and hope generated by that
summit for the acceleration of the SAARC process, it is
unfortunate that recent developments in the sub-continent have led
to increased tension in South Asia," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan carried out six nuclear tests on May 28 and 30 in
response to the five nuclear tests conducted by India on May 11
and 13, raising fears of a nuclear arms race in the region.
</P>
<P>
"As the current chairman of SAARC, I call upon all parties
concerned to exercise maximum restraint, and to make every
possible effort to contain the situation," Gayoom said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the parties to begin the process of informal
political consultations agreed upon at the 9th SAARC summit in
order to create a climate of confidence and trust in the region,
which he said would allow regional cooperation to go ahead
unimpeded.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan,
India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
