<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Scientist Lists Major Science Events in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS)
President Lu Yongxiang today reviewed the major events in
China's scientific development in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a conference attended by CAS academicians, Lu said
that the century has witnessed unprecedented scientific and
technological developments around the world, and that mankind's
scientific thinking and methods have matured.
</P>
<P>
He noted that reform and opening-up over the past two decades
have pushed China's scientific and technological development to
a new stage.
</P>
<P>
The president listed the following ten major events in the
process of China's science development in this century:
</P>
<P>
First, along with the New Culture Movement early in the
century, a number of scientists returned from overseas and
some institutions of higher learning were established, which laid
the foundation for modern scientific development in China.
</P>
<P>
Second, with the setting up of scientific organs, including the
Central Research Institute and the Beiping (-- old name of
Beijing) Research Institute in the late 1920s, the foundations of
the basic disciplines of mathematics, physics and chemistry were
laid, and China's scientific undertakings began to get on a
regular track.
</P>
<P>
Third, the newly-founded People's Republic of China in 1949
decided to organize the Chinese Academy of Sciences, which pooled
large numbers of outstanding scientists and invited back many
scientists living overseas. A national science and technology
system with CAS at the core was formed.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, in 1956 China worked out and began to implement a
12-year science program, founding a number of new science and
technology research centers, and establishing a basic
framework for science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Fifth, China's petroleum industry took off, mainly due to the
efforts of Chinese scientists and engineers themselves.
</P>
<P>
Sixth, the development of nuclear weapons and China's own
man-made satellite not only safeguarded national security but also
boosted the self-confidence of the Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
Seventh, achievements such as the development of synthetic
bovine insulin and research into Goldbach's conjecture showed the
world the ability and creativity of the Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
Eighth, the Report Outline of the Chinese Academy of Sciences
was mapped out in 1975, under the guidance of Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Ninth, a national congress on scientific development was
held in 1978.
</P>
<P>
And tenth, the development of science and technology in China
has entered a new period since the country's introduction of
overall reform and opening to the outside world, and the reform of
the science and technology system.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the theory that "Science and technology
constitute a primary productive force", which was put forward by
Deng Xiaoping a dozen years ago, has greatly boosted scientific
undertakings in China.
</P>
<P>
"People in science and technology circles have reached
the consensus that the pace of building a new scientific and
technological system in China must be quickened in the face of
economic globalization and the forthcoming knowledge-based
economy," Lu Yongxiang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
