<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
here Monday appointed three economists as senior economic advisers
to help the government reverses the economic downturn, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
"Economic issues are given top priority, the government is
determined to deal with them," State Secretary/Minister Akbar
Tanjung said.
</P>
<P>
The three senior economic advisers, Widjojo Nitisastro, Ali
Wardhana and Frans Seda, were tasked to given suggestions to the
head of state and ministers under the Coordinating Minister for
Economy, Finance and Industry on how to solve the crisis and
future economic issues, Tanjung said.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks of unrests have gravely aggravated the economic
crisis in the country, as reflected by the steady decline of the
rupiah which is now only worth a quarter of its 1997 value. Many
factories have stopped production, unemployment is continue rising
and the cost of daily necessities have now hit an exorbitant
level.
</P>
<P>
At the end of a fact-finding visit to Indonesia last Saturday,
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) Asia Pacific Director Hubert
Neiss said he has no reason to doubt forecasts that the battered
Indonesian economy could contract 10 percent or more in 1998.
</P>
