<HEADLINE> Kaunda Walks to Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's detained former president
Kenneth Kaunda who has been charged with misprison of treason here
was set free Monday morning together with his security chief Moyce
Kaulung'ombe after the state withdrew its case.
</P>
<P>
Lusaka high court judge Japhet Banda said the court forgave
Kaunda and his security chief the offenses they committed 10
minutes after the court opened. Kaunda was charged with
concealing knowledge of a coup plot last year.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, who led Zambia for 27 years from independence until
he was ousted by Frederick Chiluba in multiparty elections in
1991, denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of supporters of Kaunda and his opposition United
National Independence Party (UNIP) were signings and dancing out
the court as soon as Kaunda walked out of the court.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda,74, was detained last December for alleged involvement
in last october's foiled military coup which aimed to topple the
elected Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
he was formally charged together with his security chief with
misprison of treason, the legal term for not reporting knowledge
of a treasonous act, last February. Junior army officers staged
an abortive coup attempt against Chiluba in October.
</P>
<P>
Some people believed that freedom for Kaunda, who has been
under house arrest for most of the time since his detention, came
as part of a deal brokered by South African President Nelson
Mandela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
