<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is to hold donors
conference in London soon to help children affected by the war in
Sierra Leone, a report reaching here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Olara Otunnu, the U.N.'s special representative for children
and armed conflict, was quoted as saying this Saturday in
Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, at the end of his four-day
visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu, who met President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and members of
parliament in his visit, said he was appalled "to see a
congregation of unaccompanied children emerging from bushes with
no clothes, no food" during his visit to Daru in the east of the
country.
</P>
<P>
"I am concerned about all children in armed conflicts
situation not only child soldiers, ex-combatants or displaced but
also those who have lost their limbs and those who have been
traumatized," he added.
</P>
<P>
Afflicted by years of civil war, Sierra Leone is now one of
the poorest country in the world.
</P>
<P>
The country's military junta, who overthrew elected president
Kabbah last May but was driven out from Freetown in February this
year, is still fighting the west African peace-keeping force
ECOMOG in the east. The war has produced tens of thousands of
refugees and displaced people. 
</P>
