<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Pay to Raise ADB Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa would pay 475
million Rand (93 million U.S. Dollars) over the next eight years
to finance its increased stake in the African Development Bank
(ADB), Deputy Finance Minister Gill Marcus said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Marcus announced last week South Africa's intention to raise
its share-holding in the ADB to six percent from one percent
after the bank's share holders struck a deal to increase its
general capital by 35 percent and to change the bank's voting
structure.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's pledge amounts to a contribution of 7.4 billion
Rand (1.45 billion Dollars) to the Abidjan-based bank, Business
Day paper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 475 million Rand to be paid over the first eight years,
about 67 million Rand (13 million Dollars) will be paid every
year in the first five years and 45 million Rand (8.8 million
Dollars) will be paid annually in the remaining three years.
</P>
<P>
Marcus described South Africa's move as reflecting a profound
confidence that the bank, after three years of institutional
reforms, would be the driving force of an "African renaissance".
She said payment would begin in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The ADB would have a "very positive and exciting" role in
searching for special measures to assist countries emerging from
conflicts, such as Rwanda, the Democratic Republic of Congo and
Liberia, she said.
</P>
<P>
The bank could provide not only financial aids, but also
technical assistance, knowhow and support that these countries
need to stabilize and improve their economies, Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
She said South Africa would continue to participate in the
African Development Fund, the bank's soft loan window, to the
tune of 36 million Rand (7 million Dollars) at present.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was newly accepted as the second African
contributor, after Botswana, to the African Development Fund.
Talks were taking place to allow more African governments to
finance the fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
