<HEADLINE> Kenyan Varsities' Intake Goes up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's five public universities
enrolled a total of 45,591 students in the 1997-98 academic year,
up 14.8 percent compared to the previous academic year.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of female students enrollment improved from
28.8 percent to 29.2 percent during the period, according to a
press report issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
Those who were pursuing postgraduate studies make up 9.8
percent of the total enrollment, said the report.
</P>
<P>
With 15,400 students, the University of Nairobi has the
highest enrollment, constituting 35.4 percent of the total intake
and followed by Kenyatta University, with 9,461 (21.7 percent)
students, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Maseno University College however recorded the lowest
enrollment of 2,809 (6.4 percent) students in the 1997-98
academic year.
</P>
<P>
Enrollme at the Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture
and Technology recorded a remarkable increase of 34.5 percent to
stand at 3,005 in the 1997/98 academic year.
</P>
<P>
In the year, Moi University, located in Kenya's western city
Eldoret, enrolled a total of 4,810 students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
