<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President-Elect Cleared in Slaying Plot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Justice of the
Philippines Monday finally cleared president-elect Joseph Estrada
of any link with an alleged plot to assassinate outgoing President
Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after Under-Secretary Jesus Zozobrado
made a recommendation to Justice Secretary Silvestre Bello saying
there was no sufficient evidence to link Estrada to the alleged
plot.
</P>
<P>
Estrada was dragged into the alleged slaying plot during
election campaigns. One of his top aide said Estrada smuggled
high-power guns into the country and ordered him three times to
kill Ramos in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Estrada denied the allegation, saying the aide
was being investigated by policemen for involving in kidnappings.
When the national police looked into the alleged plot, the aide
fled to other countries.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, the presidential candidate of the main opposition
Laban ng Makabayang Masang Pilipinos (Fight of Patriotic Filipino
Masses), won a landslide victory in the May 11 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
Estrada will be sworn in on June 30 when Ramos' six-year term
expires. Ramos was banned by law to seek a second term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
