<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Increase Defense Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Kampala has received approval from
donors to increase the share of defense spending in the coming
1998/99 budget, the first time the World Bank to allocate
substantial funds from the national budget to defense spending.
</P>
<P>
However, the government did not release the exact figure.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the Ministry of Finance were quoted by national
press as saying that donors have pledged 250 million U.S. Dollars
as budgetary support to Uganda in the new financial year
beginning June 1.
</P>
<P>
The budget is to be presented on June 11, 1998 by the new
Minister of Finance and Economic Planning Gerald Sendawula.
</P>
<P>
"There is a general sense of agreement from the donor
community that the government may spend substantial amounts of
money on defense because we recognize the problem of insecurity
in parts of the country," said Randolph Harris, the World Bank
resident representative in Kampala.
</P>
<P>
He noted that donors were satisfied the defense expenditure
would not encroach substantially on funds earmarked for social
programs like education, health and road rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
The defense spending reportedly takes the lion's share of
Uganda's budget, followed closely by universal primary education,
transport and health.
</P>
<P>
The government is intensifying its fight against the rebels of
the Lord Resistance Army (LRA) in the north and those of the
Allied Democratic Forces in the west.
</P>
<P>
Recent infiltration into Kitgum and Gulu districts in north
Uganda by LRA rebels spearheaded by Joseph Kony hit headlines and
army units have been dispatched to the areas from other districts
in a decisive campaign against the rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
