<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Weak in Thin Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Last Friday's fall on Wall Street
and lower Asian bourses dragged the Australian share market to a
weaker finish Monday amid thin trading.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index ended 26.6 points, or almost
1 percent, softer at 2689.1, but up from its intra-day trough of
2675.2.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 70.25 points on Friday to
8,899.95, capping off a volatile week in which 214 points were
slashed from the index.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, the Nikkei shed 349.75 points or 2.2 percent to close
at the day's low of 15,321.03 due to renewed worries about the
health of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said concerns over how New York and Asian markets would
perform this week dominated local investor sentiment.
</P>
<P>
"The market is just extremely cautious right now and much will
depend on what happens offshore over the week," Reynolds &AMP; Co's
Peter Struk said.
</P>
<P>
He said market speculation was resurfacing over a possible rate
cut in Australia, which helped the All Ordinaries' partial
recovery.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was contained to 231.88 million shares valued
at 697.75 million Australian dollars (432.6 million U.S. dollars),
with 741 falls and 383 steady outpacing 314 rises.
</P>
<P>
The industrials sector slid 49.8 points to 4676.9 while the
resources index dropped 7.2 points to 1092.1.
</P>
<P>
BHP bucked the trend to climb 14 cents amid rumors that the
resources giant was poised to announce a high-profile candidate to
replace former chief executive John Prescott.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto shed 14.4 cents, Comalco tumbled 35 cents or 5.7
percent, Caltex lost 17 cents and MIM dipped 2 cents.
</P>
<P>
Among the industrials, Foster's firmed 3 cents, Coca-Cola
Amatil ended 21 cents down, Westfield declined 20 cents,
Woolworths moved back 2.3 cents and Mayne Nickless fell 21.1
cents.
</P>
<P>
Australia's big four banks all lost ground, driving the index
51.7 points lower to 5881.5. NAB forfeited 14.4 cents, Westpac
shed 13.6 cents, ANZ fell 16.9 cents and CBA came off 12 cents.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks eased as bullion traded in Sydney 20 U.S. cents
weaker at 292.1 U.S. dollars an ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
