<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar on the Slide Again as Japanese Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar was pushed
back below the 62 U.S. cent level Monday as the Japanese yen
continued to plunge against the United States dollar.
</P>
<P>
The local currency fell as low as 61.88 U.S. cents before
stepping back up a little to close at 62.02 U.S. cents from
Friday's close of 62.34.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank senior manager for foreign exchange Kurt
Magnus said the Japanese yen/US dollar exchange rate was very
close to its previous record low, reached on July 5, 1991, of
139.35.
</P>
<P>
"We've just hit that now," he said moments before the close of
the market locally.
</P>
<P>
Magnus said the Australian dollar continued to be used as a
proxy for weakening Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
"The interrelation between the Japanese yen and the Aussie
remains at historically high levels and any weakness in the yen
will see weakness in the Australian dollar," he said.
</P>
<P>
As the Japanese yen fell against the U.S. dollar it would push
the Australian dollar back to last week's near-12 year low of
61.65 U.S. cents, Magnus said.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar was at 86.20 from
86.41 against Japanese yen and 1.1022 from 1.1107 against German
mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
