<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Determined to Protect Intellectual Property: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) government is determined to protect
the creative talent of both local people and overseas investors,
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa said here today.
</P>
<P>
Seizures of pirated optical discs in the first five months of
this year, amounting to more than 28 million, exceeded those made
in the entire 1997, the top leader of Hong Kong told the opening
ceremony of the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO)
Asian Regional Symposium.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium, held in HKSAR for the first time,
focuses on the enforcement of intellectual property rights in the
context of implementing the Agreement of Trade-Related Aspects of
Intellectual Property (TRIPS) under the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
"Effective enforcement can only flow from good laws. Our set of
laws on protection of patents, designs, trademarks and copyright
works is one of the most complete and modern in the world," Tung
noted.
</P>
<P>
"That, of course, is not enough in itself. Like many other
economies, we face considerable challenges in our efforts to
enforce these laws," he continued.
</P>
<P>
Tung pointed out that, on top of the legislative and
enforcement efforts, the government "will do more in educating our
traders not to take part in illegal activities which infringe
intellectual property rights, and our general population not to
demand cheap, pirated or counterfeit goods."
</P>
<P>
The departments concerned have been reaching out to secondary
school students and the community to help them understand the
importance of intellectual property protection, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, co-organized by the WIPO and the Intellectual
Property Department of the HKSAR, is attended by more than 100
professionals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
