<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Three Ruling Party Alliance Collapses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan's three-party ruling alliance
of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), the Social Democratic
Party (SDP) and the New Party Sakigake broke up Monday with the
SDP's departure.
</P>
<P>
The SDP formally decided to quit the four-year-old ruling
coalition at a meeting Saturday of its lawmakers of both houses of
the Diet (parliament).
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Saturday, the SDP mentioned differences
between the LDP and the SDP over an anti-corruption bill and the
cabinet approval of new Japan-U.S. defense cooperation-related
bills without the SDP's agreement.
</P>
<P>
The SDP's decision to quit the alliance ends the tripartite
system which dates from the establishment in June 1994 of the
three-party coalition government with the then SDP leader Tomiichi
Murayama as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting of the heads of the three parties Monday morning,
SDP chairwoman Takako Doi conveyed her party's decision to leave
the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Sakigake has also decided to leave the alliance at the end of
the current session of the Diet, scheduled to last through June 10.
</P>
<P>
No immediate change in the country's governing structure is
expected as the LDP controls a majority in the powerful House of
Representatives (lower house), analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The LDP, however, may experience some difficulties in the House
of Councillors, where the ruling party lacks a majority, they said.
</P>
<P>
Ryutaro Hashimoto, leader of the LDP, succeeded Murayama as
prime minister in January 1996 but the SDP and Sakigake maintained
the three-party coalition.
</P>
<P>
After the launch of the second Hashimoto cabinet last
September, the two parties remained as the LDP's non-cabinet
parliamentary allies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Talks to Go On Under New Philippine Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) - Peace talks between the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) and the administration of new Philippine
President Joseph Estrada will continue even if the process might
be delayed a little.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed Monday by a high-ranking MILF official amid
fear and speculations by various sectors regarding the fate of the
peace process under the new government.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chair for political affairs and also
chairman of the MILF peace negotiating panel, said over a local
radio station that they are only awaiting signals from their
counterpart in the government to continue the talks.
</P>
<P>
Asked how the reshuffling plan of the new government for the
peace negotiators would affect the pace of the talks, Jaafar said
he is confident that though it would delay the process a bit, the
plan surely would not bring the negotiations back to square one.
</P>
<P>
So far, the only concrete result achieved in the talks is the
cessation of hostilities between the MILF forces and the Armed
Forces of the Philippines, including the Philippine National
Police.
</P>
<P>
Before the May 11 national elections, the government and MILF
peace panels got entangled with the issue of the identification of
some 43 MILF rebel camps in Mindanao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
