<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Celal Talabani, leader of northern Iraq's Patriotic Union
of Kurdistan (PUK), has said that Turkey's cooperation with the
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) impedes peace process in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The PUK and KDP have been fighting each other for dominating
northern Iraq since the regime of Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
lost its effective control of the region in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Sabah (Morning):
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi is due
to pay a one-week visit to the United States in mid-July in an
effort to further bilateral military ties.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Washington, Karadayi is expected to meet
with U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen and Chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff Henry Shelton as well.
</P>
<P>
Yeni Yuzyil (New Century):
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey might suffer a decrease of around 25 percent in the
number of European visitors, especially Germans and Britons, this
summer due to the upcoming 1998 World Cup in France, Turkish
officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
They believe that most Europeans would rather go to Paris or
stay at home watching TV than to spend their vacation in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Radikal (Radical):
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem and State Minister Sukru Sina Gurel in charge of the European
Union (EU) affairs will meet this week to work out a plan for
improving Turkish-EU relationship.
</P>
<P>
Ankara refused to attend the Turkish-EU Association Council
meeting on May 25 in Brussels on the grounds that the European
organ still adopts "a discriminative policy" toward Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
