<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air France Pilots Start Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- All the pilots of Air France began an
indefinite strike Monday, 10 days before the start of the
Football World Cup finals to be held in France.
</P>
<P>
The pilots are protesting a plan by the company's management to
 cut their salaries by 15 percent in exchange for the company's
stocks.
</P>
<P>
They are also protesting the non-application of an agreement
signed earlier which abolishes salary disparity between young and
old pilots.
</P>
<P>
The traffic of Air France was almost non-existent Monday
morning, while only one plane flew from the Orly airport in Paris
to Corsica and another from the Charles de Gaulle airport to
Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
Air France cancelled 90 percent of its long-distance flights
from Paris, and 75 percent of medium-distance flights.
</P>
<P>
On the international airlines, it is expected to guarantee one
plane to Africa and three to the United States.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 passengers who have booked Air France plane seats
on their way home from the Pentecost holiday are expected to be
stuck on their way or change to trains and cars.
</P>
<P>
Two other French air companies, the private AOM and Air Liberte
have few extra seats to offer, although they plan to open more
home flights from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The state railway company SNCF also said its train seats are
fully ordered.
</P>
<P>
Air France, which has invested millions of francs to be
designated as the official air transporter for the Football World
Cup finals, said that they will guarantee the transport of the
national football teams even if the strike continues.
</P>
<P>
But the transport of fans and spectators will not be
guaranteed, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
