<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Holds Talks with His Turkish Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
has voiced that the Chinese government attaches importance to its
relations with Turkey and will join it in pushing forward
bilateral friendship and cooperation on the basis of the Five
Principles of Peaceful Co-Existence.
</P>
<P>
In his talks here today with Turkish Deputy Primer Minister
Bulent Ecevit, who arrived here on May 30 as guest of the Chinese
government, Qian said that the two countries should keep exchanges
at various levels and strengthen coordination and cooperation in
regional and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Noting that both China and Turkey are countries with a long
history and they enjoy a traditional friendship, Qian said that
the Chinese side is satisfied with the smooth development of
Sino-Turkish friendly and cooperative relations in various fields
since the two countries forged diplomatic ties in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed his appreciation for Turkish government's
efforts in developing Sino-Turkish relations and for Turkish Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz's recent statement to the effect that
developing relations with China is one of the stresses in Turkish
foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed out that the establishment of a long-term and
stable Sino-Turkish friendship and cooperation oriented to the
21st century is not only in the fundamental interests of the two
peoples, but also conducive to peace and stability in the region
and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that both Turkey and China boast ancient
civilizations and their bilateral friendly relations in various
aspects have acquired satisfactory progress.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Turkish government places great
importance to its relations with Asia, especially with China,
fully respects China's territorial integrity, and will raise
bilateral friendship and cooperation to a new level along with the
Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
They also exchanged opinions on international and regional
issues of common concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
