<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 08:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Wounded, 110 Arrested in Lebanon's Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 10 Lebanese were wounded
on Sunday in clashes among the knife or club waving supporters of
rival candidates in the second round of Lebanon's first local
elections in 35 years, the Daily Star newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The scuffles had led to the arrest of 110 people in North
Lebanon governorate. In the first round of polls in the
governorate of Mount Lebanon, the country's central province, 14
people were detained for fist fight.
</P>
<P>
But Interior Minister Michel Al-Murr put the best face on what
he termed a "trouble-free" day by saying the army and security
presence had quickly quashed the incidents.
</P>
<P>
The government has been seeking to maintain a peaceful
electoral atmosphere in order to avoid further violence or
disturbances which Lebanon had suffered during its 1975-1990
sectarian civil war.
</P>
<P>
During the polls, armored personnel carriers mounted with
machine guns were stationed on major intersections and troops
stood outside the polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Some candidates have begun to criticize the government's
irregularities and interference in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Ex-premier Omar Karame accused Prime Minister Rafik Hariri of
engaging in vote-buying in the contest of Tripoli, the nation's
second largest municipality after the capital of Beirut. He
expected the results to be announced Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's elections started on May 24 and will continue on the
following two Sundays in Beirut, eastern province of Bekaa Valley
and South Lebanon. The Israeli-occupied border strip is not
included in this elections.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said that the hottest race will take place in
the polls in Beirut where at least a third of the whole population
live. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Agrees to Concessions for Ugandan Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Ports Authority (KPA)
and the Kenya Revenue Authority have extended concessions to
Ugandan importers using Mombasa, Kenya's commercial hub and a
leading Indian Ocean port in east Africa.
</P>
<P>
The changes include the cancellation of 100 percent
verification of Uganda-bound containerized cargo, the East
African weekly newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The move follows a visit last month to Kenya by Ugandan
Minister Abel Rwendeire to complain about trade barriers which
frustrated Ugandan traders importing goods through Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan customs officials would put seals on Uganda-bound
containers as soon as they arrived at the port, but should there
be any sign of interference with the seal, the containers would
be subject to verification.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan clearing agents welcomed the scrapping of the 100
percent verification, which they blamed for the loss and damage
of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
Ismail Mboya, the KPA resident representative in Kampala, said
the concessions have been introduced to bring the Ugandan
shippers to the same queue with their Kenyan colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan cargo enjoys an eight-day free period for
documentation, compared to four days for Kenya's imports.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan imports also enjoy four-day free storage, while Kenyan
imports are allowed for two days.
</P>
<P>
The KPA also agreed to allocate a special area for
Uganda-bound containers at the Mombasa container terminal.
</P>
<P>
"Given the congestion at the port, it may not be easy to
provide the required space now. However, it was agreed that the
KPA will undertake to provide that space in between three and six
months," said Mboya.
</P>
<P>
Before Rwendeire's visit, executives of the Uganda Clearing
and Forwarding Agents Association have met with the chief of the
Kenya Revenue Authority.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan importers and clearing gents requested the KPA to
give tariff concessions, provide a special storage area for
Uganda-bound containers and issue motor inspection reports to
Ugandan motor vehicle importers.
</P>
<P>
The agents also complained about pilferage at the port.
</P>
<P>
In response, Mboya said measures have been taken to improve
security at the port, including stricter controls at entry and
exit gates, improved surveillance and sealing of unauthorized
routes.
</P>
<P>
The KPA plans to put an electric fence around the perimeter
wall and to build watch towers at the vehicle section.
</P>
<P>
Like Rwanda, Burundi, southern Sudan and eastern Democratic
Republic of the Congo, landlocked Uganda uses Mombasa port
extensively for its imports and exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Launching of Mir Gyro Thrusters Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The launching of gyro thrusters of
the Russian Mir space station, originally scheduled for Monday
morning, has been put off until the afternoon, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The gyro thrusters, which automatically maintain the station's
pitch and attitude to ensure that the solar panels generate
maximum power, failed after the station's main computer was
replaced with a new one Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The old main computer aboard the Mir crashed on Saturday night,
for the second time this year. The first computer crash occurred
on January 2.
</P>
<P>
As the mission control center in Korolyov near Moscow could not
have the solar panels reoriented toward the sun with the gyro
thrusters, Mir's orientation will be maintained by the engines of
the station itself.
</P>
<P>
Before the orientation returns to normal, the cosmonauts will
have to conserve energy.
</P>
<P>
The latest malfunction has caused alarm on whether the
scheduled docking with the U.S. Discovery shuttle would go as
planned, but flight commander Vladimir Solovyov told the Interfax
news agency that the computer failure would not hinder the U.S.
mission.
</P>
<P>
The situation "is not so complicated" and Mir's solar panels
are generating sufficient energy for the station's operation,
Solovyov said.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia has notified the U.S. mission control in
Houston, Texas, of Mir's readiness to receive the mission to be
launched from Cape Canaveral Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo Monday
on renewed uncertainty about the domestic and other Asian
economies.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange plummeted 349.75 points or
2.23 percent from last Friday's close to finish at 15,321.03.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 24.79 points or 2.03 percent to
1,196.70.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 320 million
shares, unchanged from Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nikko Securities was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Following the release late last week of gloomy Japanese
economic figures for March and April, an 8.0 percent drop in new
vehicle sales in May from a year earlier, which was reported
Monday afternoon, depressed the Tokyo market, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Plunges on the Hong Kong and Taibei bourses also weighed on
Tokyo stocks, they said.
</P>
<P>
Shares were sold almost across the board. Of the 1,335 issues
listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered gainers 889 to 222
gained, with 135 remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
