<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Train Its Own Seamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will soon
start training its seafarers to conform with international
maritime requirements as the International Safety Management
(ISM) Code deadline of July 1 draws closer.
</P>
<P>
So far only 130 out of Kenya's 5,000-strong seamen have
received training that could enable them to survive the ISM Code
deadline, the East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Major maritime nations around the world have promised tough
measures against any ship that fails to comply with the ISM Code,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Merchant Shipping Superinterdent Captain John Martin
Odhach, was quoted as saying that plans were under way for
seafarers to be issued with acceptance certificates to enable
them to work on foreign ships.
</P>
<P>
The planned course, which he said would be held at the Kenya
Ports Authority-owned Bandari College, will be conducted in line
with the International Maritime Organization (IMO) course
modules.
</P>
<P>
Odhach said arrangements were also being made to have locally
registered vessels audited and issued with relevant certificates.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan seafarers have long expressed concern about the recent
implementation of new training standards set by the IMO through
the revised Standards of Training and Certification and Watch
Keeping.
</P>
<P>
Officials of Seamen's Association of Kenya claimed that some
Kenyan seafarers have lost their jobs on ships under German,
Singporean and British flags as a result of the new convention.
</P>
<P>
"Many more are likely to follow and we urge our government to
come to our aid," the association's Secretary-General John Ayanga
said.
</P>
<P>
The associ was reportedly to be raising 35 million
Shillings (64,000 U.S. Dollars) to train some of its 5,000 plus
members, most of whom are at Bandari College, a local maritime
institute.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan seamen have always complained of poor pay in foreign
ships, earning only 200 Dollars a month compared with their
foreign colleagues who earn between 450 and 600 Dollars, due to
lack of training.
</P>
<P>
The new IMO demands could increase cases of stowaways from the
region as potential seafarers unable to obtain employment on
foreign-registered ships will be tempted to get aboard illegally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
