<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Can't Afford AIDS Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has imported some anti-AIDS
drugs but they cannot reach average AIDS patients in Uganda
because the drugs are too expensive.
</P>
<P>
The drugs, which are selling at between 12,000 and 15,000 U.S.
Dollars in the east African country, are beyond the means of
ordinary patients who earn some 100 Dollars a months.
</P>
<P>
The newly-imported drugs, including saquinavir, ritonavir,
indinavir and nelfinavir, can not only slow down the
multiplication of the HIV virus but also reduce its concentration
in the blood, downgrading AIDS from a terminal illness to a
chronic disease, the latest edition of East African weekly
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government has adopted a multi-sectoral approach
in its fight against AIDS, putting main energy and money on
information and education to increase people's awareness of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
According to an estimate by the Ministry of Health, 10 percent
of Uganda's population are infected with the virus and some
500,000 patients have died since the first case was reported in
the country in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Uganda AIDS Commission, Omwony Ojwok,
said there are over 30 million people infected with HIV/AIDS
worldwide, 60 percent of whom are in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Globally, 10,000 new infections are occurring daily and 90
percent of all new cases during 1997 are in the sub-Sahara
region, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
