<HEADLINE> Uganda Chooses Power Dam over Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has ended
its hesitation over building a power dam or developing tourism at
the Bujagali Falls in Jinga east of here by choosing the latter.
</P>
<P>
Monday's East African weekly based in Nairobi quoted Fred
Kallisa-Kabagambe, the permanent secretary in the Ministry of
Energy and Minerals, as saying that the government thinks
electricity is a more urgent priority for the country's economy
than a white water rafting project.
</P>
<P>
"It is a question of priority. You cannot have rafting and
remain in darkness," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier studies showed that the Bujagali was the best place
for a hydro-electricity dam with minimal impact on the
environment, he added.
</P>
<P>
A joint venture between the United States and Uganda, the
power station to be built will cost 460 million U.S. Dollars and
have a capacity of 290 megawatts of electricity annually.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's demand for power stands at 230 mw, of which the
Uganda Electricity Board produces 180 mw.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Finance said the Ugandan
economy would have been growing at nine percent instead of the
current seven percent, had it not been for power shortages.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a New Zealand-based water rafting company said the
falls is the best place for water rafting, adding that it will
generate up to 25 million Dollars a year, more than 20 percent of
the country's tourism income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
