<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Aggressors' Military Maps on China Made Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 150 military maps drawn by
Japanese before their aggression on China (1937-1945) were
recently made public in this capital city of central China's Hubei
province.
</P>
<P>
Local residents say the maps have offered new evidence for
Japanese long-premeditated aggression war against China.
</P>
<P>
All the counties and cities and most towns in the province are
indicated on the maps, which are drawn to the scale of 1:50,000.
</P>
<P>
For instance, on the map of Qianjiang county, all the villages,
towns, mountains and rivers in the county and its neighboring
counties are carefully drawn.
</P>
<P>
Most of the maps bear the word "military secrets" on
the right top and "Land Survey Department" on the left
bottom.
</P>
<P>
Experts say most of the maps are drawn by Japanese and some
are made by Chinese but collected by Japanese aggressors.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Kaiyuan, a historian who last year released some
important documents about Japanese atrocities in China, said: "It
is very obvious that the Japanese army drew the maps for their
aggression on China."
</P>
<P>
The oldest of those maps was drawn in 1929. "So they had
prepared for the war for at least eight years," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The maps were found by a retired official of a bus company on a
flea market in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Reclaim Land from Taklimakan Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese farmers in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region have reclaimed 600,000 million
hectares of arid land and opened up 26,000 hectares of farmland in
Taklimakan Desert in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 farmers have resettled in Hotan, southern tip of
China's largest desert.
</P>
<P>
Over 40,000 hectares of diversiform-leaved poplars and 93,000
hectares of Chinese tamarisks in the reclaimed land have formed a
shelterbelt network in the area, which used to suffer from most
serious windstorms in the country.
</P>
<P>
When 35-year-old Abudul Keram resettled in the desert area four
month ago from an oasis, he was not sure if his family could have
a living there.
</P>
<P>
After he saw that his newly planted forage grass and trees
around his courtyard were growing very well, he became confident
of his future. He said he can not only have more farmland, but
also can breed more cattles for his new home.
</P>
<P>
Liu Minting, an expert in the field of desertification control,
said that Hotan Prefecture has become an area that witnesses
China's most tangible achievements in desert reclamation.
</P>
<P>
Hotan has won an award from the United Nations Development
Program for its efforts in desertification control.
</P>
<P>
Liu said experiments have indicated that grain crops can be
grown two years after forage grass, trees and melons are
planted. otherwise grain crops would be buried by floating sands.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that another key factor involved in the desert
reclamation is the installation of water-saving irrigation system.
</P>
<P>
With his help, some farmers in Hotan introduced Israel's drip
irrigation technique in an orchard and the local government has
decided to spread the foreign technique.
</P>
<P>
Half of Xinjiang's land are desert or desertification
land. More than two thirds of the Taklimakan Desert are located
in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
