<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Illegal Oil Dealers Turn to L. Victoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Dealers in illegal trade in oil
products in Kenya have turned to Lake Victoria to transport their
goods following a crackdown on them by security authorities.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown was ordered by President Daniel arap Moi in late
February, when he said that traders caught dumping fuel meant for
export should be arrested, the East African weekly reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The racket involves businessmen collecting oil products from
the Kenya Pipeline Company (KPC)'s Kisumu depot, ostensibly for
export, which enables them to avoid paying millions of Shillings
in duty, and dumping them on the local market.
</P>
<P>
The traders fabricate tankers, which are then mounted onto
boats to ferry their products.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government loses about 1.4 million Shillings (about
23,000 U.S. Dollars) for every 60,000 liters -- the capacity of
an average tanker -- of oil dumped on the local market.
</P>
<P>
Security officials and Kenya Railways Corporation said they
had received complaints from Uganda and Tanzania, to which the
illicit trade had extended.
</P>
<P>
Nyanza Provincial Commissioner Peter Raburu confirmed last
Tuesday that there would be a crackdown on governmental officials
who issued the traders with documents to facilitate their
business.
</P>
<P>
Raburu ordered an immediate ban on transportation of oil
products by boat across the world's second largest fresh water
lake.
</P>
<P>
Regional Traffic Superintendent of Kenya Railways Festus Araka
said his organization has suspended any transfer of oil products
from trucks onto boats at all beaches on the Kenyan side of the
lake.
</P>
<P>
Oil products will now only be exported in Kenya Railway
tankers and ferried by the four specially designated vessels that
ply the lake.
</P>
<P>
The initial crackdown came immediately after Moi's order which
has resulted in nationwide arrests of traders engaged in the
illegal business and those operating unlicensed fuel stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
