<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China ferreted out 1,229 smuggling
cases in the first quarter of this year, according to
Beijing-based magazine "Outlook", which was published here today.
</P>
<P>
The number of smuggling cases on the sea increased by 81
percent compared with a year ago, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
Top on the list of smuggled goods were raw materials for
chemicals, oil, autos and spare parts, cashmere, edible oil, steel
and computers.
</P>
<P>
Most of the smuggling cases were seized in south China's
Guangdong province, Beibu Gulf in Guangxi, Haikou city in Hainan
province, Xiamen, Quanzhou and Fuzhou cities in Fujian province,
and Dalian in northeast China's Liaoning province.
</P>
<P>
China's Customs, public security, industrial and commercial
departments will combine their efforts to combat the growing
number of smuggling, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
In June, the country is to convene a national anti-smuggling
conference during which more effective measures will be worked out
to crack down on smuggling cases, it added.

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
