<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading South African newspapers Monday:
</P>
<P>
The Citizen:
</P>
<P>
-- The trial of apartheid hard liner P. W. Botha resumes
Monday after a six-week break, with Truth and Reconciliation
Commission chairman Desmond Tutu set to testify against the
former president.
</P>
<P>
-- African countries such as South Africa and Nigeria should
develop nuclear weapons to defend themselves against other
countries around the world if these countries did not want to
disarm, opposition Pan Africanist Congress leader Motsoko Pheko
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Star:
</P>
<P>
-- South Africa is poised to deliver, worldwide, a new
generation of environment-friendly, safe, "pocket-sized" nuclear
power stations which can be placed on factory premises or in
municipal areas.
</P>
<P>
-- The new chief of the South African National Defense Force,
General Siphiwe Nyanda, hinted broadly at the weekend that the
proposed 12-billion-Rand (2.35-billion-U.S. Dollars) procurement
of new defense equipment may be trimmed or even delayed.
</P>
<P>
Business Day:
</P>
<P>
-- South African exports to the United States surged in the
first quarter of this year, slashing South Africa's trade deficit
with the U.S. 
</P>
