<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Constructing Flood-Control Command Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
province has been stepping up efforts to build a province-wide
modern flood-control command network.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, prospecting and designing of two
separate microwave telecommunications projects at Dahuofang and
Liaobei reservoirs, with a total investment of 15 million yuan,
are carried out.
</P>
<P>
The two projects, which are important parts of the projected
modern flood-control command network this northeastern province
wants to build, will be completed next year.
</P>
<P>
The microwave telecommunications project at Taizi River,
another important part of the future flood-control command network
and costing an investment of 20 million, has been just finished
and has passed appraisal.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the province also plans to build a new
microwave telecommunications project in the province's central
area in bid to use modern flood-control command network facilities
to screen the eastern and central areas where Liaoning's floods
are nurtured.
</P>
<P>
Local flood-control command offices of the province's 14 cities
will be connected by computers this year. Computerization at the
provincial flood-control headquarters will be completed within
this year.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has started to upgrade more than 300 local
flood-reporting stations since 1996 and has so far finished half
of the work, said a local official.
</P>
<P>
He added that Liaoning will see a great improvement in the
efficiency of its efforts to combat floods when the modern
flood-control command network is built, coupled with the use of
the public telecommunications network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
