<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greene, Jones Chalk up Double Wins in Prefontaine Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- American world champions Maurice
Greene and Marion Jones produced excellent results to take double
wins each in the Prefontaine Classic Grand Prix athletics meet in
Eugene, Oregon of the United States, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Greene kept his word to beat the men's 100 meters world record
with in a blazing 9.79 seconds -- one of the fastest clockings in
history -- but only upset to see the trailing wind of 2.9 meters
per second was well over the legal limit of 2.0.
</P>
<P>
Greene's training partner, Ato Boldon of Trinidad, was second
in 9.89.
</P>
<P>
Greene went on to do big later, beating world record-holder
Michael Johnson of the United States in the 200 meters with a
clocking of wind-aided 19.88 seconds. This time the wind was
recorded at 2.1 meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Jones, who won the women's 100 meters at the world
championships in Athens last year and clocked a year's best 10.71
early this month in China, ran a wind-aided 10.78 to win the 100
meters.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old muti-talent shifted to the long jump following
her sprint win, soaring a mingty 7.31-meter leap, a wind-legal
mark that is the best in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
If not for the wind, Greene said, Donovan Bailey's 100 meters
world record of 9.84 seconds would have fallen.
</P>
<P>
"It would have been broken," Greene said. "It would have been
broken."
</P>
<P>
It matched the third-fastest 100 meters ever under all
conditions, behind Obadele Thompson's 9.69 at altitude and Carl
Lewis's wind-aided 9.78 in 1988 in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
Andre Cason ran two wind-aided 9.79 clockings during the USA
Track and Field Championships here in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Greene was especially pleased with his victory over Johnson in
the 200.
</P>
<P>
Johnson is "the best 200 runner in the world. It's always great
to run against the best," Greene said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't ever go anywhere to lose. When I step on the line, I
expect to win," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jones, who ran a world-leading 10.71 seconds in China earlier
this year -- second-fastest of all-time behind only Florence
Griffth-Joyner's world record of 10.49 -- said she was pleased
with Sunday's performance.
</P>
<P>
"The time was OK," Jones said. "I'm happy with it.
</P>
<P>
"Considering this is like the start of the summer, it's a good
way to start. The crowd here is awesome. It prepares me for
Europe."
</P>
<P>
In addition to Jones's long jump, the IAAF Grand Prix meet
produced several marks that are the best in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 5,000, Kenyan Luke Kipkosgei outlasted countrymen
Julius Gatahi and Simon Maina, clocking 13:07.83.
</P>
<P>
In the men's mile, Kenya's Daniel Komen attempted to become the
first person to run under 3:50 on American soil. He settled for
the second-fastest mile ever in the United States, 3:50.95, best
in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
In non-Grand Prix events, American world champion Allen Johnson
won the 110-meter hurdles in a world-leading 13.12 seconds, and
Maria Mutola of Mozambique won the women's 800 in 1:58.66, also a
world-leading time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
