<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minor Quakes Still Possible But Not Major Ones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The possibility of minor
earthquakes in Beijing still exists, but that of serious ones
measuring above five on the Richter Scale is very little in the
near future, according to a Chinese leading seismologist.
</P>
<P>
Ding Jianhai, director of the Earthquake Warning Center
attached to the State Seismological Bureau (SSB), said, "Although
the earthquake measuring 3.4 on the Richter Scale hitting around
Fengtai District early this morning was slightly bigger than the
two ones last night, it does not mean that bigger, destructive
ones will follow up."
</P>
<P>
"All the three quakes are the normal adjustments of the
Zhangbei earthquake happened in north China early this year."
</P>
<P>
Ding added that quakes measuring from three to five on the
Richter Scale shocking regions within 200 km around Zhangbei in
Hebei Province are all normal adjustments.
</P>
<P>
"No adjustments in the area will be abnormal, and could
probably mean major quakes later," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Ding said that minor earthquakes will not threaten Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Beijing was hit by two minor quakes measuring 3.1 on the
Richter Scale at 7:37 and 7:42 Sunday evening, followed by another
one measuring 3.4 on the Richter Scale early this morning. Tremors
were felt in Fengtai, Haidian and Shijingshan districts.
</P>
<P>
These were the first quakes that can be felt happened in the
capital this year. Beijing has been hit by one to three such
quakes every year since 1996. Its Tongxian County in the east
suburb was shocked by a quake measuring 3.1 on the Richter Scale
on December 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The State Seismological Bureau is keeping a close eye on the
crustal movements around Beijing, home to China's most advanced
earthquake monitoring network which can record slight quakes
measuring as low as one on the Richter Scale.
</P>
<P>
"Each slight irregularity will be compared with past records,
and analyzed," said Ding, adding that experts have regular
meetings on earthquake forecasting.
</P>
<P>
"The State Seismological Bureau will issue its forecasts to the
public when quakes measuring above five on the Richter Scale are
possible to take place."
</P>
<P>
Records show that the capital has never been hit by earthquakes
measuring above seven on the Richter Scale.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-Pak Arms Race Threatens SAARC: Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Nuclear arms race between India and
Pakistan would threaten the existence of the seven-nation SAARC
(South Asian Association of Regional Cooperation), a press report
Monday quoted speakers as saying at a seminar here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The economic hardship descending on the two countries would
make way for an integrated economic cooperation in the region for
their very existence, State Minister for Foreign Affairs Abul
Hasan Chowdhury pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The seminar on sub-regional cooperation in South Asia was
organized by the Bangladesh Institute of international and
Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
Following the incidence of nuclear tests, the SAARC had been
posed with a new question, Chowdhury said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no alternative to cooperation," the state minister
said. Bangladesh as a pioneer of the SAARC would pursue "very
productively" to put together all resources and bring about an
attitude of economic escalation in the SAARC region.
</P>
<P>
"Nuclear tests are hardly conducive to regional cooperation,"
Professor Abul Kalam of International Relations of Dhaka
University said. The nuclear tests by India, followed by Pakistan,
infused "a fear of cold war in the region".
</P>
<P>
A massive fall in the region's external funding for economic
development would also follow, Kalam predicted.
</P>
<P>
"A far-sighted leadership with vision and perspective can only
translate the dream of the people of the region into economic
cooperation," Kalam stressed.
</P>
<P>
The future of the SAARC had become uncertain in the context of
detonation of nuclear weapons by both India and Pakistan, former
bureaucrat Mujibul Huq pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
