<HEADLINE> Old Age Allowance Program Launched in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina Sunday launched the old-age allowance program to help the
elderly people and remove poverty from rural areas of the country,
press reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering of old men and women in the southwestern
town of Tungipara Sunday, Hasina said the government had taken up
such a program so that the neglected rural poor could be benefited
directly.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to remove all sorts of discrimination,
exploitation, poverty from rural areas of the country," she said
before handing over the pass books of the allowance program to the
elderly people.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the elderly people would receive 100 taka
(about 2.2 U.S. dollars) each per month.
</P>
<P>
The money, even though very little, would help them raise their
status in the family and society, make them feel that they were
still important, she added.
</P>
<P>
On the first day, about 450 old people of Tungipara received
their allowances, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government had enlisted over 400,000 people from
4,479 unions under 461 sub-districts of the country to bring them
under the scheme. 
</P>
</TEXT>
