<HEADLINE> Japan Gives Sri Lanka Irrigation Machinery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan has supplied Sri Lanka
irrigation machinery worth about 8.7 million U.S. dollars under
the second stage of funding the Nagdeepa and Minipe irrigation
schemes.
</P>
<P>
The machinery was handed over last weekend by Japanese
Ambassador Yoji Sugiyama to Irrigation and Power Minister Anurudha
Rattwatte, the ministry sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the machinery was supplied from the balance
funds provided under a credit line by the Japan's Overseas
Economic Corporation Fund (OECF) for 18,750 million yen (407.6
million U.S. dollars) provided in 1991 for the rehabilitation of
headwork and main canals at Nagdeepa and Minipe in the Central
province of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The work, completed in 1998, sees 6,170 hectares in Minipe and
1,791 hectares in Nagdeepa rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
The new equipment will be used for the operation and
maintenance of the two projects, the sources added. 
