<HEADLINE> Romania Issues 100,000-leu Bank Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian National Bank put in
circulation Monday the 100,000-lei bank notes, each worthing about
12 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This biggest-ever bank note was initially scheduled for
issuance last summer but was postponed because of the unexpected
high inflation of 151 percent in 1997, sources of the National
Bank said.
</P>
<P>
Romania's previous biggest bank note had a denomination of
50,000 lei.
</P>
<P>
Bank leaders do not think the issuance will contribute to
high inflation rate, which the Romanian government vowed to rein
in to below 45 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Though considering it an ambitious target, bank experts agree
the inflation rate this year would be remarkably lower than 1997.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show a gradual inflation drop this year, with the
April figure standing at 2.7 percent, or 1.1 point down from
March. 
