<HEADLINE> Cambodian First PM Leaves for Visit to Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian First Prime Minister
and Minister for Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation Ung
Huot left here Monday for Vietnam for a two-day official visit at
the invitation of Vietnamese Premier Phan Van Khai.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to hold talks with Vietnamese officials on the
issue of Vietnamese immigrants in Cambodia, the common land
border, the overlapping areas of rich maritime resources as well
as bilateral trade, culture and education relations.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot is also expected to review the Vietnam-Thailand
agreement that touches upon Cambodia's territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached on August 9, 1997, dividing the
maritime boundary between Vietnam and Thailand in the Gulf of
Thailand, including their new continental shelf boundary as well
as the boundary between their economic zones.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian Foreign Ministry sent a diplomatic note to Thailand
and Vietnam on February 7, protesting the agreement for violating
its sovereignty. Early last month during his official visit to
Bangkok, Second Prime Minister Hun Sen also expressed his
objection to the agreement. 
