<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls Survive in Game 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan scored 28 points
and Toni Kukoc added 14 of his 21 in the third period as the
Chicago Bulls held off the Indiana Pacers 88-83 in the decisive
game of the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls, who lost three of their previous four games in the
series and were forced to the brink of elimination, kept cool and
sharp in the final minutes, beating the Pacers 4-3 and earned a
rematch with the Utah Jazz in the NBA Finals. Game 1 is on
Wednesday in Salt City.
</P>
<P>
"We came out a little tense, a little nervous, but came back in
the ballgame and we knew we were in a fight," Jordan said. "A lot
of people say we sit back and wait for me but today everybody had
to step forward and do it."
</P>
<P>
The battle was a cliff-hanger and it all came down to the final
five minutes. Jordan and the team displayed intensity and control,
scoring nine of the game's final 13 points.
</P>
<P>
The game was tied 79-all going into the final five minutes, and
that is when the Bulls showed their rich experience. Scottie
Pippen, who scored 17 points, made a jumper after grabbing one of
Chicago's 22 ofensive rebounds, and Jordan drew a double-team and
fed Luc Longley for a corner throw.
</P>
<P>
Jordan suffered a poor shooting accuracy in the first period,
scoring only two points, but finished the first half with 15, and
the Bulls led the half time 48-45.
</P>
<P>
Besides 28 points, Jordan also grabbed nine rebounds, eight
assits and two steals. Kukoc contributed 13 of 21 points in the
third quarter, followed by Pippen's 17 points, 12 rebounds, three
assistes and two steals.
</P>
<P>
Reggie Miller led Indiana with 22 points, shot in all his first
three-pointer balls, but failed to do anything in the fourth
quarter as Jordan guarded him tightly.
</P>
<P>
Chicago dominated the rebounding by grabbing 50 to Indiana's
34. The pacers looked sharp at the start, building up a 20-7 lead
en route to a 27-19 advantage after one period.
</P>
<P>
Jordan surpassed Kareem Abdul-Jabbar's career playoff scoring
record of 5,762 points in the second quarter. When the Indiana
missed eight of its first 10 shots in the quarter to fall behind
40-33, the Pacers fate was doomed.
</P>
<P>
Facing Utah next Wednesday, Jordan said: "Utah is back there
waiting for us and they have the homecourt and it'll be even
tougher. A day off will gives us a chance to clear our minds and
focus." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
