<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12th Asia-Pacific Roundtable Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The 12th Asia-Pacific
Roundtable opened here Monday with a call for finding ways and
means to remove deep-seated suspicions and hostility between
states.
</P>
<P>
Opening the three-day Roundtable themed "Confidence Building
And Conflict Reduction", Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim said, "Few moments are more challenging than the present"
for talking about confidence building and conflict reduction and
calling for finding ways and means to remove deep-seated
suspicions and hostility between states.
</P>
<P>
"We believe only civil society can provide a framework for the
removal of suspicion and distrust and heal the wounds of history.
Thus, the promotion of civil society must be the prime concern of
diplomacy in Asia," he said in his keynote address.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also Malaysia's finance minister, said a healthy
state-civil society relationship will contribute to the reduction
of differences in political practices, strengthen the marketplace
and promote freedom, and a culture of democracy, founded on
"universal principles of liberty", is the sine qua non for peace
in this world.
</P>
<P>
He said the Asian economic crisis came about because of an
incompatibility between the Asian national systems and the
international system.
</P>
<P>
More than 230 people from 20 countries in the Asia-Pacific
region and international institutions are attending the
Roundtable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
