<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Plywood Exports to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's foreign exchange
earnings from plywood exports is expected to decline 25 percent
this year, caused by sluggish demand and a reduction in
production, According to The Jakarta Post Monday.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that the Association of Indonesian Wood Panel
Producers (Apkindo) expected that the country's foreign exchange
earnings from plywood exports is about 2.6 billion U.S. dollars
this year, compared with 3.58 billion U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Apkindo chairman Abbas Adhar said that many Indonesian plywood
producers cut their production this year following sluggish demand
and an increase in production costs.
</P>
<P>
"If the market remains unfavorable throughout the year, plywood
exports are expected to stand at about 2 billion U.S. dollars, a
record low since 1990," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is the world's biggest plywood producer, turning out
10 million cubic meters of plywood annually. Last year, Indonesia
exported 7.58 million cubic meters of plywood and set the target
to export 8 million cubic meters this year.
</P>
<P>
Due to the declining volume of Indonesian plywood in the past
few months, Abbas said, some plywood importing countries had
started buying plywood from Malaysia, the world's second biggest
plywood producer.
</P>
<P>
But Abbas is optimistic that Malaysia will not replace
Indonesia's position due to its higher prices. "Malaysian plywood
is more expensive because the price of their logs is higher than
ours," Abbas added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
