<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Food Program Helps China's Ethnic Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Xihaigu in the
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, one of China's impoverished
areas, have notably improved their life with the help of a
free aid project by the World Food Program (WFP).
</P>
<P>
The WFP project, coded 4071, was started in 1994 in 13
townships in three counties, is aimed at improving local natural
conditions and help farmers escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
By now, WFP has provided 51,049 tons of grain, with local
governments injecting 30 million yuan of investment as well as
labor services.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 9,236 hectares of hillsides have been transformed
into terraced fields, 8 reservoirs reinforced, and 2,274 hectares
of irrigated land added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, per-capita farmland has been raised from 0.04 ha to
0.1 ha, with annual grain output and farmers' per-capita net
income growing by 50 percent and 78 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Some environment-friendly projects have also been built,
and accordingly, a 484-square-kilometer area has been improved to
reduce 1.41 million tons of eroded soil annually.
</P>
<P>
The project has also boosted construction of local
infrastructure and applications of practical farming
techniques. More than 60,000 farmers have been trained to use such
techniques. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Civil War Displaces 800,000 People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing civil war between Tamil
rebels and government troops has displaced a total of 800,847
persons in the northern and eastern provinces, according to
official sources Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sources in the Reconstruction and Rehabilitation Authority
for the north said these people belonged to 195,195 families as of
April 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 796,079 are in 15 refugee centers in several
districts and the rest are staying with their friends and
relatives or running the streets.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government spends 24.7 million rupees (392,000
U.S. dollars) per month on dry rations with the assistance of the
World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has long been plagued by problems between the
Sinhalese and the Tamil, the two major ethnic groups in the island
country.
</P>
<P>
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have been fighting
against the government for a separate Tamil state in the north and
east of the country since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Government troops recaptured Jaffna Peninsula in May 1995.
Since then some 200,000 refugees have returned to their homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Real Estate to Take Off Because of Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China's housing industry is
expected to generate more than 0.5 percents to gross
domestic product (GDP) this year and beyond, according to a senior
State economist.
</P>
<P>
Hu Shaowei, the economist with the State Information Center,
said pending housing reform will increase housing's role in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
"The boost in housing investment since the beginning of this
year and the possible increase in housing consumption after July 1,
when China abolishes the welfare housing distribution system, will
be two major forces to achieve the 0.5 percent in GDP growth," he
said.
</P>
<P>
China invested 52.1 billion yuan (6.3 billion U.S. dollars) in
its real estate sector in the first four months this year, up 12.7
percent from the same period in 1997. The investment in April
alone rose 19.1 percent from last year's level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, with more than 50 million square meters of
apartments standing empty nationwide -- the fruit of billions of
dollars in bank loans -- there is ample supply available after the
planned housing reform.
</P>
<P>
The reform could unleash vast demand for residential housing,
which was suppressed by the welfare housing system and
insufficient development of the commercial residential housing
market, said Gu Yunchang, vice-director of the policy and research
center of the Ministry of Construction.
</P>
<P>
China's housing reform will have three major tasks --
abolition of welfare housing distribution, building the secondary
market and improvement of the residential housing construction
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
