<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0230 GMT, June 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said Sunday that
most Arab countries have endorsed a Palestinian proposal to hold
an Arab summit to coordinate stances on the stalled Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return to Gaza from a two-day visit to the United Arab
Emirates (UAE), Arafat told reporters that "very important effort"
is being made to convene the summit very soon because of the
critical situation the peace process is facing.
(Palestinian-Arafat-Arab Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Chairman of the Japanese Joint Chiefs of Staff Kazuya
Natsukawa arrived here Sunday on an eight-day official visit to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency said the visit, the first ever by the
top Japanese military leader, would be packed with "numerous
meetings" with Russian military officials. (Russia-Japan-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- After triggering a nuclear arms race in South Asia
by detonating five nuclear devices, India on Sunday proposed that
all nuclear weapons states and the international community open
negotiations for a nuclear weapons convention.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued this evening by the Ministry of External
Affairs said that the convention is necessary to deal with these
weapons in a global non-discriminatory framework as the other two
weapons of mass destruction had been through the biological
weapons convention and the chemical weapons convention.
(India-Nuclear Weapons)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel and his Iranian
counterpart Kamal Charrasi have agreed to meet on June 10 in New
York on the sidelines of the U.N. Special General Assembly in a
bid to mend bilateral relations, the German Foreign Ministry
announced Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The June 10 talks had been agreed upon by the two foreign
ministers during a telephone conservation on Sunday, the foreign
ministry said. (Germany-Iran-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An Islamic organization and the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) have expressed deep concern for the nuclear tests by India
and Pakistan and urged them to take measures to keep security and
stability in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, Secretary
General of the Organization of the Islamic Conference Ezzidine
Laraki said that his organization "has always been looking forward
to the establishment of a nuclear-free region in South Asia," the
Kuwaiti News Agency reported on Sunday. (Egypt-Nuclear-Reaction)
</P>
