<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Property Projects put on Hold in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economic and political
uncertainty has put more commercial property projects on hold in
the second quarter of this year, according to a study published
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The latest study, issued by property consultants First Pacific
Davies Indonesia (FPDI), showed that many projects stopped as
economic and political uncertainty mounted.
</P>
<P>
"The majority of projects have been suspended for an indefinite
period, while others have slowed down and have revised completion
dates," the study said.
</P>
<P>
The retail sector has been worst hit, with almost all new
retail projects put on hold until 2001, according to the study.
Some 93 percent of the nearly 475,000 square meters of retail
developments previously planned have now been suspended.
</P>
<P>
In the office sector, over one million square meters or 66
percent of the confirmed developments have been put on hold.
Delayed projects are expected to increase to 84 percent of the
confirmed developments by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
In the hotel sector, most of the hotel projects put on hold are
four-star hotels. Construction of 72 percent of the three-star
hotel developments is going on, the study said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
