<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Allows Philippines to Post Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government may be
allowed to post a budget deficit this year instead of a surplus,
as long as it is able to post a current account surplus.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) had indicated that it may
be willing to accept a budget deficit "for as long as the
Philippines posts a current account surplus", the Philippine Star
Monday quoted Assistant Finance Secretary Gil Beltran as saying.
</P>
<P>
An IMF mission which conducted a review of the country's first
quarter economic performance over the weekend found the country's
monetary performance satisfactory, but the fiscal sector below
par.
</P>
<P>
The national government had projected a 5 billion pesos (128
million U.S. dollars) budget surplus this year, but first quarter
cash budget performance was quite poor, registering an 11.7
billion pesos (300 million dollars) deficit instead.
</P>
<P>
The government's main revenue generating agencies have failed
to reach their revenue targets partially because of the regional
currency crisis which resulted in lower income tax payments by big
corporations.
</P>
<P>
Despite these setbacks, Beltran remains optimistic that the
government can still post a budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
The basis for optimism, according to Beltran, is the
improvement in the country's macroeconomic indicators which would
allow the government to realize some savings.
</P>
<P>
Beltran cited the downward trend in Treasury bill rates and the
stability of the Philippine peso in recent months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
