<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Real Estate Market Recovered from Stagnation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China's real estate market had
recovered from a year of stagnation by the end of April, suggested
the China Real Estate Comprehensive Index.
</P>
<P>
The Index climbed up to 100.81 points in April, up 1.76 from
March or up 2.59 points from April, 1997, according to a report
from the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months, the real estate investment totaled
52.1 billion yuan (6.3 billion US dollars), a year-on-year
increase of 12.7 percent. This growth rate was higher than that of
infrastructure and renovation, and higher than March's growth rate.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the country started housing construction of
34.78 million square meters, up 44.0 percent from the same period
of 1997, and 11 percent from that in March.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sales price rose continually in the past several
months as a result of surging demand. The average sales price for
commercial housing was 2,091 yuan per square meter in February,
2,124 yuan in March and 2,258 yuan in April.
</P>
<P>
Though the acreage for land development continued to drop as a
result of the country's restriction on non-farming use of land,
the decrease rate slowed.
</P>
<P>
The index is expected to pick up further in the first half of
this year, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Sets Poverty Elimination Target by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is to reduce the number of
poverty-stricken families to 10 percent of its total
by year 2000, Vietnam News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The government will boost the national program for Hunger
Eradication and Poverty Alleviation (HEPA) activities to provide
all communes and villages with basic infrastructures, especially in
transport and communications, elementary education and primary
health care.
</P>
<P>
Since HEPA started its operations in 1995, it has mobilized
over 3 trillion V.N. dong to lend to more than two million
families nationwide and has helped reduce the number of
poverty-stricken households.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics, 13 percent of all communes
and wards in the country remain stricken by hunger and poverty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Urged to Restore Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Moslem leader Amien Rais
called on the new government to take steps to overcome the
economic crisis, according to press reports here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering at the Bogor Institute of Agriculture in
Bogor, about 60 kilometers south of the capital, Sunday, Rais also
called for public support to the new government.
</P>
<P>
It is unfair to blame everything on the new government as many
of the difficulties are a legacy of the previous government, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The new government led by President B.J. Habibie was
established on May 22 after Soeharto resigned.
</P>
<P>
"What would be fair, in order to set the economic wheels moving
again in the shortest possible time, is giving an opportunity and
support for economic-restoration programs," Rais said.
</P>
<P>
This stance, he said, does not mean the campaign for better
order in the political, legal and constitutional system should
stop.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the country's second largest Moslem organization
reiterated that a general election should be held soon.
</P>
<P>
"State policies, including in the economy, are, after all, the
final results of an interaction of various interest groups,
political forces, the business circle as well as the bureaucracy,
which all operate in a certain legal-constitutional order," Rais
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
