<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States, Russia Keep Winning Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BREMEN, Germany, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
Russia both kept unbeaten streak, while China were edged by
Lithuania at the Women's World Basketball Championship here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
WNBA star Lisa Leslie got a game-high 21 points and 12
rebounds, leading the United States to a 79-68 victory over Spain.
</P>
<P>
The Americans, winners at the Atlanta Olympic Games, met a
strong challenge in the first half and trailed 7-13 before they
bursted with a 13-2 run to regain the lead at 20-15. They hang
onto the lead to the end.
</P>
<P>
Russia built a 5-0 record after trouncing Asian runners-up
Japan 103-76 as Elena Nikonova tossed in a game-high 19 points and
nine rebounds and guard Nadeja Mrilova added 18.
</P>
<P>
Pre-game favorite Russia met little trouble and took a 50-36
halftime lead, and then enlarged their advantage to as many as 30
points at 83-53 on Mrilov's lay-up with 8:48 to play.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania, helped by guard Loreta Berukstlene's 18 points,
squeezed China to win their first second-run game 72-70.
</P>
<P>
The Lithuanians, whose best center was injured before the
championship and who had lost three games to the United States,
Japan and Russia, played a tough game throughout and led the first
half 38-32.
</P>
<P>
China, led by center Zheng Haixia with 24 points and 11
rebounds, had a chance to equal or win the game at last several
seconds as Jiang Xue, who scored a 3-pointer with 30 seconds left
to make it 70-72, missed another 3-pointer attempt.
</P>
<P>
China, only 1-4 holders in group E, play Japan Monday while
Lithuania meet Spain and Russia take the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
