<HEADLINE> Jazz Works and Waits for its Final Opponent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Following another hard practice
yesterday, Utah Jazz's coach Jerry Sloan let the team take a day
off Sunday before it begins to prepare for the NBA final round,
which starts Wednesday in Salt City.
</P>
<P>
Utah expects to be ready no matter which team wins Game 7 of
the Eastern Conference finals in Chicago today. The Jazz coaching
staff has already prepared extensively for the Bulls and the
Pacers, and the players have been briefed on their match-ups
against each team.
</P>
<P>
The Jazz say such a long wait, the second-longest ever between
the conference finals and the finals, isn't a complete good thing.
</P>
<P>
"The first game is very important for us, because we have to
get our game face on from the first minute," Karl Malone said.
</P>
<P>
The Jazz has been keeping busy and working very hard during
their waiting period following its 4-0 rout of the Los Angeles
Lakes in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
The team played a full scrimmage, officated by CBA referees, at
Delta Center and looked sharp and fresh in high spirit. 
</P>
