<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aussies Retain Field Hockey World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Holders Australia came from one
goal down to beat hosts the Netherlands to retain the World Cup
trophy at this year's tournament for women in Utrecht on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Australia beat the Netherlands 3-2 while Germany downed
Argentina with a similar scoresheet to finish third at the 12-team
tourney.
</P>
<P>
In the previous cup tourney four years ago, Australia blanked
Argentina 2-0 to win the cup.
</P>
<P>
Ellen Dubbeldam-Kuipers grabbed an opening-minute chance to put
the hosts on the scoreboard and the Dutch held on to the early
lead with a partisan chanting by home fans.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic champions, however, proved their form and flair in
the sport by more than offseting the deficit as Alyson Annan and
Julie Towers netted two goals within two minutes in the 22nd and
24th to turn the tide.
</P>
<P>
Juliet Haslam, a 29-year-old 2000 Olympic coordinator, put the
game further away from the hosts with a 56th-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
A 62nd-minute goal scored off a penalty corner by defender
Julie Deiters re-kindled the hope of the Dutch side to steal the
coveted trophy from the Aussies.
</P>
<P>
But the Australians held on to their lead until the final buzz.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands won the women's World Cup five times and
finished runners-up twice.
</P>
<P>
In the day's placing games, Olympic silver medalists South
Korea defeated New Zealand 4-3 to finish fifth behind Argentina
while South Africa outshot the United States 4-2 on the penalty
spot after their scoreless regular play. The World Cup debutants
from Africa were placed seventh.
</P>
<P>
Ninth through 12th places went to England, Scotland, China and
India that played their playoffs a day earlier on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
