<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lithuania Edge China 72-70 in Basketball Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BREMEN, Germany, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Lithuania, helped by guard
Loreta Berukstlene's 18 points, held off Chinese counterparts'
strong rally to win their first second-run game 72-70 on Sunday at
the women's world championship for basketball.
</P>
<P>
China, led by center Zheng Haixia with 24 points and 11
rebounds, had a chance to equal or win the game at last several
seconds as Jiang Xue, who scored a 3-pointer with 30 second left
to make it 70-72, missed her another 3-pointer attempt, sending
Lithuania to take two team standing points from the game.
</P>
<P>
The Lithuanians, whose best center was injured before the
championship and who had lost three games to the United States,
Japan and Russia, played a tough game throughout and led the first
half 38-32.
</P>
<P>
China opened the second half with 14-0 run within 3:30. The
Chinese scored four 3-pointers in the span, with forward Yangli
and guard Zheng Dongmei each hitting two.
</P>
<P>
However, the European champions levelled the score 52-52 on
Berukstlene's basket with 11:30 remaining.
</P>
<P>
Exchanging lead several time, Lithuania seemed to win the game
when it took over 72-67 with four minutes to play. But Jiang Xue's
3-pointer made Lithuania in danger.
</P>
<P>
"I am satisfied with our performance especially at the
beginning of the second half," said Ma Yuenan, Chinese head
coach. "Our team are young and need experience. Now we will
prepare for the game against Japan and we will go all out for a
win."
</P>
<P>
China, only 1-4 holders in group E, play Japan Monday while
Lithuania meets Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German, Iranian Foreign Ministers to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
and his Iranian counterpart Kamal Charrasi have agreed to meet on
June 10 in New York on the sidelines of the U.N. Special General
Assembly in a bid to mend bilateral relations, the German Foreign
Ministry announced Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The June 10 talks had been agreed upon by the two foreign
ministers during a telephone conservation on Sunday, the foreign
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Germany and Iran entered into a diplomatic dispute in April
last year after a German court ruled that Iranian leaders had
ordered the killings of four Kurdish dissidents in a Berlin
restaurant in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The ruling prompted European Union countries to withdraw their
ambassadors to Teheran and suspend the so-call critical dialogue
with the country.
</P>
<P>
After a seven-month standoff, the two sides agreed to put an
end to the crisis and all EU ambassadors had returned to Teheran
by November last year.
</P>
<P>
During the telephone talks on Sunday, Kinkel and Charrasi
agreed to make efforts to further improve relations. They also
expressed satisfaction at the results of a recent high-level
contact between German and Iranian officials in Teheran, the
German foreign ministry said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
