<DOCNO> XIE19980601.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leaders Reject Royal Party Invitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein leaders Gerry Adams and
Martin McGuinness turned down an invitation on Sunday to a Belfast
garden party at which Prince Charles will be guest of honor,
according to BBC report.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that members of Sinn Fein, the political
wing of Irish Republican Army, have been invited to the
Hillsborough Castle garden party, the main social event of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein said its leaders would not go because of the Prince's
links to the British Parachute Regime which was responsible for
Derry's Bloody Sunday killing of a dozen Catholics.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam earlier in the day
defended her decision to invite Sinn Fein leaders to a Northern
Ireland garden party, arguing that the invitation had been part of
the peace process in the province because Sinn Fein had signed up
to the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The decision to invite the meeting between Adams and Charles,
however, sparked outrage from opposition politicians in Britain
and from Protestant Unionists who said Mowlam was being
insensitive.
</P>
<P>
Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble said: "I think the
secretary of state will be relieved at their absence, particularly
after the republican-orchestrated violence in Portadown."
</P>
<P>
He added that the only time Sinn Fein leaders could be invited
would be when they ceased to be terrorist leaders and became
democratic ones.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
